WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:19.188 align:middle line:90%


00:00:19.188 --> 00:00:21.874 align:middle line:90%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:21.874 --> 00:00:24.040 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA GARR: Imagine living
for two and a half years

00:00:24.040 --> 00:00:29.020 align:middle line:84%
eating only edible ground plants
in a teepee in the Ozarks.

00:00:29.020 --> 00:00:31.360 align:middle line:84%
That's what my next guest
and leading herbalist

00:00:31.360 --> 00:00:34.570 align:middle line:84%
did when she grew up with
over 50 years of experience

00:00:34.570 --> 00:00:38.160 align:middle line:84%
as a nutritional consultant
of natural health.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:41.200 align:middle line:84%
Brigitte Mars has over
14 books and teaches

00:00:41.200 --> 00:00:44.500 align:middle line:84%
at Naropa University and
prestigious institutes

00:00:44.500 --> 00:00:46.570 align:middle line:90%
around the world.

00:00:46.570 --> 00:00:49.660 align:middle line:10%
Hi, I'm Lisa Garr, and master
herbalist Brigitte Mars

00:00:49.660 --> 00:00:52.870 align:middle line:10%
is here to share her vast
knowledge of living close

00:00:52.870 --> 00:00:55.550 align:middle line:10%
to the earth and a few very
special recipes, as well.

00:00:55.550 --> 00:00:56.350 align:middle line:90%
Welcome.

00:00:56.350 --> 00:00:58.058 align:middle line:84%
>>BRIGITTE MARS: Thank
you so much, Lisa.

00:00:58.058 --> 00:01:00.520 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I love your
knowledge-- your vast knowledge

00:01:00.520 --> 00:01:02.980 align:middle line:84%
of the Earth and
the plants on it.

00:01:02.980 --> 00:01:06.550 align:middle line:84%
What drew you to this,
this incredible resource

00:01:06.550 --> 00:01:09.040 align:middle line:84%
that we have right
underneath our feet?

00:01:09.040 --> 00:01:10.540 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I was really
blessed to have

00:01:10.540 --> 00:01:13.270 align:middle line:84%
this wonderful French
Canadian grandmother,

00:01:13.270 --> 00:01:15.580 align:middle line:84%
and she didn't call
herself an herbalist,

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:17.410 align:middle line:90%
but she was definitely wise.

00:01:17.410 --> 00:01:20.309 align:middle line:10%
And I remember one time
walking in the woods with her.

00:01:20.309 --> 00:01:21.850 align:middle line:10%
She knew the names
of all the plants,

00:01:21.850 --> 00:01:26.620 align:middle line:10%
and we found this little wounded
bird, and she picked it up.

00:01:26.620 --> 00:01:29.560 align:middle line:84%
And we brought it home, and
she fed it some special herbs

00:01:29.560 --> 00:01:32.550 align:middle line:84%
and put salve on it, and a few
days later it could fly away.

00:01:32.550 --> 00:01:34.630 align:middle line:84%
And I must have
been three or four,

00:01:34.630 --> 00:01:37.190 align:middle line:84%
but I said I want to
be able to do that.

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:40.060 align:middle line:84%
And I grew up in
the '50s, and so it

00:01:40.060 --> 00:01:44.320 align:middle line:84%
was a lot of injections
and antibiotics,

00:01:44.320 --> 00:01:47.890 align:middle line:84%
and I really preferred the
remedies of my grand-mere,

00:01:47.890 --> 00:01:49.060 align:middle line:90%
as I called her.

00:01:49.060 --> 00:01:49.860 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Oh.

00:01:49.860 --> 00:01:52.600 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Apple cider vinegar
and honey or peppermint tea.

00:01:52.600 --> 00:01:54.940 align:middle line:84%
And my grandmother's
idea of ice cream

00:01:54.940 --> 00:01:58.159 align:middle line:84%
was to put maple syrup
that we made on snow,

00:01:58.159 --> 00:01:59.950 align:middle line:84%
and there was this
connection to the Earth,

00:01:59.950 --> 00:02:03.520 align:middle line:84%
and it really seemed like
something out of a fairy tale,

00:02:03.520 --> 00:02:05.320 align:middle line:84%
and really medicine
for the people.

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:06.850 align:middle line:84%
It made all the
sense in the world

00:02:06.850 --> 00:02:08.660 align:middle line:90%
that we should all know this.

00:02:08.660 --> 00:02:11.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Well, how far have
we gotten away from it?

00:02:11.320 --> 00:02:16.030 align:middle line:84%
I mean it's how people have
lived for thousands of years.

00:02:16.030 --> 00:02:19.940 align:middle line:84%
It's not anything that we
shouldn't already know to do,

00:02:19.940 --> 00:02:21.282 align:middle line:90%
but it's been undone.

00:02:21.282 --> 00:02:22.990 align:middle line:10%
>>MARS: It's been
undone, and I sometimes

00:02:22.990 --> 00:02:26.200 align:middle line:10%
think we've been bamboozled
a bit, because we think

00:02:26.200 --> 00:02:29.020 align:middle line:10%
that all our food needs
to come from the store,

00:02:29.020 --> 00:02:32.360 align:middle line:10%
needs to have a package,
directions, a barcode.

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:35.470 align:middle line:84%
And one atrocity,
Lisa, is that we

00:02:35.470 --> 00:02:38.260 align:middle line:84%
are using a third of
our nation's water

00:02:38.260 --> 00:02:42.250 align:middle line:84%
to water grass, which, unless
you're a cow or a goat,

00:02:42.250 --> 00:02:43.847 align:middle line:90%
you're probably not eating.

00:02:43.847 --> 00:02:45.430 align:middle line:84%
And I think we're
really going to have

00:02:45.430 --> 00:02:47.970 align:middle line:90%
to rethink how we use water.

00:02:47.970 --> 00:02:50.950 align:middle line:84%
A proverb I heard years ago
that I really took to heart

00:02:50.950 --> 00:02:54.590 align:middle line:84%
is, if you have water to throw
away, throw it on a plant.

00:02:54.590 --> 00:02:56.690 align:middle line:84%
And this whole idea
that we're going

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:59.680 align:middle line:84%
to have a lawn that is suitable
for nothing except maybe

00:02:59.680 --> 00:03:03.385 align:middle line:84%
croquet or something, which is
really an old school paradigm--

00:03:03.385 --> 00:03:05.260 align:middle line:84%
I think we need to be
thinking about creating

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:06.940 align:middle line:90%
more edible lawns.

00:03:06.940 --> 00:03:08.920 align:middle line:84%
And if we were to
do that, we would

00:03:08.920 --> 00:03:11.440 align:middle line:84%
find that our lawns
would proliferate

00:03:11.440 --> 00:03:14.950 align:middle line:84%
with all kinds of plants that we
could use as food and medicine.

00:03:14.950 --> 00:03:17.350 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Edible lawns--
that is a great idea.

00:03:17.350 --> 00:03:19.540 align:middle line:84%
You've got to get
the pesticides out,

00:03:19.540 --> 00:03:21.290 align:middle line:90%
and the gophers sure love them.

00:03:21.290 --> 00:03:25.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, I have some of the
healthiest gophers in my house,

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:27.790 align:middle line:84%
but this is a very
important topic.

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:31.600 align:middle line:84%
I live in California,
where it is getting so dry,

00:03:31.600 --> 00:03:34.240 align:middle line:84%
and it's evident because
of the wildfires.

00:03:34.240 --> 00:03:35.920 align:middle line:90%
Colorado, as well.

00:03:35.920 --> 00:03:39.520 align:middle line:84%
Every summer it's almost
like the whole state

00:03:39.520 --> 00:03:43.540 align:middle line:84%
goes into a blaze, and it goes
through December, Brigitte.

00:03:43.540 --> 00:03:46.270 align:middle line:84%
And it's breaking my
heart, and I don't

00:03:46.270 --> 00:03:48.280 align:middle line:90%
know how I can contribute.

00:03:48.280 --> 00:03:50.140 align:middle line:84%
As I travel up the
5 freeway, there's

00:03:50.140 --> 00:03:53.620 align:middle line:84%
all these signs about water wars
and all of these different--

00:03:53.620 --> 00:03:56.030 align:middle line:90%
I mean, it's a huge problem.

00:03:56.030 --> 00:03:58.804 align:middle line:84%
We take for granted
we can open the tap.

00:03:58.804 --> 00:04:00.970 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And I don't know
if that privilege is always

00:04:00.970 --> 00:04:01.930 align:middle line:90%
going to be with us.

00:04:01.930 --> 00:04:02.110 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I don't either.

00:04:02.110 --> 00:04:04.660 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: When I see so much
development, and population

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:08.680 align:middle line:84%
increase, and that we just
flush the amount of water

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:12.340 align:middle line:84%
that a family in a developing
nation might use in a daytime,

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:14.330 align:middle line:84%
and we do it over
and over again.

00:04:14.330 --> 00:04:17.589 align:middle line:90%
So the idea of an edible lawn--

00:04:17.589 --> 00:04:20.950 align:middle line:84%
the plants that are
considered weeds

00:04:20.950 --> 00:04:25.840 align:middle line:84%
are often really hardy, because
when we take a walk in nature,

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:28.120 align:middle line:90%
nobody watered those plants.

00:04:28.120 --> 00:04:29.560 align:middle line:90%
Nobody fertilized them.

00:04:29.560 --> 00:04:31.750 align:middle line:90%
Nobody mulched them.

00:04:31.750 --> 00:04:34.810 align:middle line:84%
They are survivors,
and in herbal medicine,

00:04:34.810 --> 00:04:36.670 align:middle line:84%
there's this beautiful
philosophy called

00:04:36.670 --> 00:04:39.340 align:middle line:90%
the doctrine of signatures.

00:04:39.340 --> 00:04:41.440 align:middle line:84%
And it's a really
ancient philosophy

00:04:41.440 --> 00:04:43.240 align:middle line:84%
that you see in
India, and China,

00:04:43.240 --> 00:04:45.730 align:middle line:84%
and Native American
tradition, European.

00:04:45.730 --> 00:04:48.280 align:middle line:84%
And it talks about
that plants tell us

00:04:48.280 --> 00:04:50.820 align:middle line:84%
what they're good for
by the way they look,

00:04:50.820 --> 00:04:52.380 align:middle line:90%
and it sounds a bit folkloric.

00:04:52.380 --> 00:04:53.180 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: No.

00:04:53.180 --> 00:04:55.570 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: But cauliflower
really is good for the brain,

00:04:55.570 --> 00:05:00.280 align:middle line:84%
and hijiki seaweed really
is good for the hair.

00:05:00.280 --> 00:05:02.335 align:middle line:84%
Blueberries are really
good for the eyes.

00:05:02.335 --> 00:05:04.210 align:middle line:84%
Kidney beans are really
good for the kidneys.

00:05:04.210 --> 00:05:08.780 align:middle line:84%
So weeds are survivors, and
they're going to help us adapt.

00:05:08.780 --> 00:05:09.580 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Survive.

00:05:09.580 --> 00:05:12.190 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: We need to
start eating plants that

00:05:12.190 --> 00:05:17.710 align:middle line:84%
have adaptive survival skills,
because we are putting way

00:05:17.710 --> 00:05:21.190 align:middle line:84%
too much emphasis on plants
that are very water intensive

00:05:21.190 --> 00:05:24.691 align:middle line:84%
and take a lot of
energy to grow.

00:05:24.691 --> 00:05:27.190 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Overconsumption is also
another issue I want to talk

00:05:27.190 --> 00:05:30.940 align:middle line:10%
with you about, because as we've
seen, the inorganic fruits--

00:05:30.940 --> 00:05:32.710 align:middle line:10%
they're losing their
color because they're

00:05:32.710 --> 00:05:37.180 align:middle line:10%
so overproduced, and they are
under ripe when they're picked.

00:05:37.180 --> 00:05:40.144 align:middle line:84%
They're shipped, and
they're frozen sometimes,

00:05:40.144 --> 00:05:41.560 align:middle line:84%
and then they're
put into shelves,

00:05:41.560 --> 00:05:45.754 align:middle line:84%
and they've already been
off the vine for two weeks.

00:05:45.754 --> 00:05:47.170 align:middle line:84%
So we're not only
eating food that

00:05:47.170 --> 00:05:48.836 align:middle line:84%
doesn't have anywhere
near the nutrients

00:05:48.836 --> 00:05:50.770 align:middle line:84%
that it had in the
'50s, when you grew up,

00:05:50.770 --> 00:05:54.220 align:middle line:84%
but we're eating food
that is spoiling quickly,

00:05:54.220 --> 00:05:55.780 align:middle line:90%
and the color is gone.

00:05:55.780 --> 00:05:58.150 align:middle line:84%
Can you tell us a
little bit about that?

00:05:58.150 --> 00:06:00.130 align:middle line:90%
Tell us the history.

00:06:00.130 --> 00:06:01.960 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Well, think about this.

00:06:01.960 --> 00:06:04.330 align:middle line:84%
Very often, when
we have a salad,

00:06:04.330 --> 00:06:08.390 align:middle line:84%
how long was that lettuce, or
kale, or spinach in the ground?

00:06:08.390 --> 00:06:13.030 align:middle line:84%
So what I feel is that, if we
were to make salad from things

00:06:13.030 --> 00:06:15.420 align:middle line:90%
that were growing in our yard--

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:17.750 align:middle line:84%
lamb's quarter,
dandelion greens,

00:06:17.750 --> 00:06:19.410 align:middle line:84%
things that were
maybe growing 5,

00:06:19.410 --> 00:06:21.610 align:middle line:90%
10 minutes before we eat them--

00:06:21.610 --> 00:06:23.650 align:middle line:84%
the amount of life
force that we could

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:28.330 align:middle line:84%
imbibe from that really makes
you feel like a superhuman.

00:06:28.330 --> 00:06:30.850 align:middle line:90%
And a lot of people are tired.

00:06:30.850 --> 00:06:32.890 align:middle line:90%
They're lethargic.

00:06:32.890 --> 00:06:34.570 align:middle line:90%
They're medicated.

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:37.570 align:middle line:90%
They feel foggy, soggy, groggy.

00:06:37.570 --> 00:06:40.060 align:middle line:84%
So I'm saying,
let's go for things

00:06:40.060 --> 00:06:43.300 align:middle line:84%
that make us feel that we
have elevated life force

00:06:43.300 --> 00:06:45.930 align:middle line:84%
and elevated chi, and that's
something I think we're going

00:06:45.930 --> 00:06:50.590 align:middle line:84%
to get from learning more about
the plants that are available,

00:06:50.590 --> 00:06:51.820 align:middle line:90%
that are saying, use me.

00:06:51.820 --> 00:06:52.870 align:middle line:90%
Use me lots.

00:06:52.870 --> 00:06:53.800 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I'm abundant.

00:06:53.800 --> 00:06:54.670 align:middle line:90%
I'm here.

00:06:54.670 --> 00:06:56.830 align:middle line:90%
I'm not being over bred.

00:06:56.830 --> 00:06:59.800 align:middle line:84%
Edible flowers-- how do you
know which ones are edible?

00:06:59.800 --> 00:07:01.130 align:middle line:90%
Is it the more color?

00:07:01.130 --> 00:07:02.510 align:middle line:90%
Can you always eat pansies?

00:07:02.510 --> 00:07:03.310 align:middle line:90%
How do you know?

00:07:03.310 --> 00:07:04.851 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, we
certainly don't want

00:07:04.851 --> 00:07:07.390 align:middle line:84%
to eat flowers that come
from a florist shop.

00:07:07.390 --> 00:07:10.900 align:middle line:84%
Very often they're imported
from other continents even.

00:07:10.900 --> 00:07:12.820 align:middle line:84%
They could be using
chemicals that are even

00:07:12.820 --> 00:07:16.000 align:middle line:90%
banned in the United States.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:18.910 align:middle line:84%
We certainly don't want to
eat inorganic flowers, which

00:07:18.910 --> 00:07:21.460 align:middle line:84%
might also be something you
get from a florist shop.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:25.930 align:middle line:84%
So growing your own flowers or
supporting those companies that

00:07:25.930 --> 00:07:27.760 align:middle line:84%
are present at the
farmer's market--

00:07:27.760 --> 00:07:29.170 align:middle line:84%
there's certainly
a lot of them--

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:31.900 align:middle line:84%
no, you can't really
rely on color.

00:07:31.900 --> 00:07:34.060 align:middle line:84%
I have a book called
"Rawsome" that

00:07:34.060 --> 00:07:36.880 align:middle line:90%
has a list of over 150 flowers.

00:07:36.880 --> 00:07:39.190 align:middle line:84%
There are some flowers
that are very poisonous,

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:41.230 align:middle line:90%
like Lily of the Valley.

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:44.740 align:middle line:84%
Roses are edible, but if
they're sprayed with pesticides,

00:07:44.740 --> 00:07:46.240 align:middle line:90%
then they're toxic.

00:07:46.240 --> 00:07:50.050 align:middle line:84%
But things like nasturtiums,
and marigold, day lilies,

00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:52.990 align:middle line:84%
the traditional
hemerocallis vulva--

00:07:52.990 --> 00:07:55.240 align:middle line:90%
you can't eat all the hybrids.

00:07:55.240 --> 00:07:58.024 align:middle line:84%
All of the mint
flowers are edible.

00:07:58.024 --> 00:07:59.440 align:middle line:84%
So it's the kind
of thing you need

00:07:59.440 --> 00:08:02.290 align:middle line:90%
to learn which ones are edible.

00:08:02.290 --> 00:08:05.500 align:middle line:84%
Pansies are edible, and
their wild relative violets

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:06.580 align:middle line:90%
are edible.

00:08:06.580 --> 00:08:08.890 align:middle line:84%
If they're organic,
and you've eaten them--

00:08:08.890 --> 00:08:12.790 align:middle line:84%
however, African violets
are in a different family,

00:08:12.790 --> 00:08:14.955 align:middle line:84%
so African violets
are not edible.

00:08:14.955 --> 00:08:17.330 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Really purple ones,
like the color of your dress.

00:08:17.330 --> 00:08:20.180 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: But it could be pink,
or red, or yellow pansies,

00:08:20.180 --> 00:08:20.980 align:middle line:90%
as well.

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:23.110 align:middle line:84%
So pansies and
violets are wonderful,

00:08:23.110 --> 00:08:26.980 align:middle line:84%
and I just made
a violet vinegar.

00:08:26.980 --> 00:08:31.385 align:middle line:84%
I put violets in white vinegar,
and it made a purple vinegar.

00:08:31.385 --> 00:08:33.220 align:middle line:90%
And it was just glorious.

00:08:33.220 --> 00:08:34.299 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wonderful.

00:08:34.299 --> 00:08:35.559 align:middle line:90%
So you reminded me of a story.

00:08:35.559 --> 00:08:38.219 align:middle line:84%
I had just moved into a house,
and there was this really large

00:08:38.219 --> 00:08:39.019 align:middle line:90%
piece of furniture.

00:08:39.019 --> 00:08:42.640 align:middle line:84%
It was a large pine
piece of furniture,

00:08:42.640 --> 00:08:44.890 align:middle line:84%
and I reached on the top
of it, and I accidentally

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:47.460 align:middle line:90%
pulled it onto myself.

00:08:47.460 --> 00:08:49.750 align:middle line:84%
It toppled onto
me, and it landed

00:08:49.750 --> 00:08:52.570 align:middle line:90%
in the inside of my calf.

00:08:52.570 --> 00:08:55.240 align:middle line:90%
And nobody was around.

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:58.330 align:middle line:84%
I scooted myself
out to the yard,

00:08:58.330 --> 00:09:01.780 align:middle line:84%
and I found this
beautiful red rose.

00:09:01.780 --> 00:09:03.625 align:middle line:90%
I ate the whole thing.

00:09:03.625 --> 00:09:07.630 align:middle line:84%
I just instinctively--
I was in so much pain,

00:09:07.630 --> 00:09:10.990 align:middle line:90%
and I ate this incredible rose.

00:09:10.990 --> 00:09:12.700 align:middle line:90%
I didn't break a bone.

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:14.240 align:middle line:90%
It barely bruised.

00:09:14.240 --> 00:09:18.580 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is a giant
pine piece of furniture.

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:21.370 align:middle line:84%
I don't know how that
happened, but it was right

00:09:21.370 --> 00:09:23.200 align:middle line:90%
where I migrated towards.

00:09:23.200 --> 00:09:27.670 align:middle line:84%
It was this gorgeous-- it
was just there to say to me,

00:09:27.670 --> 00:09:29.300 align:middle line:90%
I will heal you.

00:09:29.300 --> 00:09:31.560 align:middle line:90%
And it spoke to me.

00:09:31.560 --> 00:09:35.650 align:middle line:84%
Do flowers have that level of
vibration to heal that much?

00:09:35.650 --> 00:09:38.620 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, if you think
about flowers botanically,

00:09:38.620 --> 00:09:40.810 align:middle line:84%
they are the sex
organs of plants,

00:09:40.810 --> 00:09:42.820 align:middle line:84%
and they are really
quite powerful.

00:09:42.820 --> 00:09:46.270 align:middle line:84%
They're designed to
attract pollinators

00:09:46.270 --> 00:09:47.470 align:middle line:90%
with their fragrance.

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:51.040 align:middle line:84%
They can detract predators
also with their fragrance.

00:09:51.040 --> 00:09:53.990 align:middle line:84%
They often have all kinds
of essential oils in them

00:09:53.990 --> 00:09:56.620 align:middle line:84%
which have anti-microbial
properties.

00:09:56.620 --> 00:10:01.370 align:middle line:84%
And rose indeed is very
hydrating to the skin.

00:10:01.370 --> 00:10:05.270 align:middle line:84%
It's a traditional folk remedy
for healing a broken heart.

00:10:05.270 --> 00:10:08.830 align:middle line:10%
We know that rose hips are
really high in bioflavonoids--

00:10:08.830 --> 00:10:10.870 align:middle line:10%
the fruit from the
rose, which does

00:10:10.870 --> 00:10:12.520 align:middle line:10%
strengthen the capillaries.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:18.310 align:middle line:84%
But roses have a long tradition
of being used not only in food.

00:10:18.310 --> 00:10:24.650 align:middle line:84%
Rose water is used a lot in
many cultures in cuisine.

00:10:24.650 --> 00:10:25.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Essentially the oils--

00:10:25.950 --> 00:10:28.860 align:middle line:84%
of the rose oil is so beautiful
that when you press it

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:31.040 align:middle line:84%
and you really get
that oil there--

00:10:31.040 --> 00:10:34.334 align:middle line:84%
it's a-- I have a large
affinity with roses,

00:10:34.334 --> 00:10:36.000 align:middle line:84%
but it's everywhere,
like you mentioned.

00:10:36.000 --> 00:10:39.750 align:middle line:10%
The orange blossoms-- we
have the zucchini flowers.

00:10:39.750 --> 00:10:41.520 align:middle line:10%
They're everywhere.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:44.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And you just want to
learn which ones you can eat.

00:10:44.040 --> 00:10:46.140 align:middle line:84%
And I think there's
almost a perception,

00:10:46.140 --> 00:10:49.110 align:middle line:84%
because maybe our parents
didn't know about plants,

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:52.740 align:middle line:84%
and we would pick something,
and they'd say, wash your hands.

00:10:52.740 --> 00:10:54.450 align:middle line:90%
Throw that away.

00:10:54.450 --> 00:10:56.670 align:middle line:84%
And yes, there are
some poisonous plants.

00:10:56.670 --> 00:11:00.570 align:middle line:10%
You wouldn't want to make a
centerpiece with poison ivy,

00:11:00.570 --> 00:11:05.100 align:middle line:10%
or ingest poison hemlock or
water hemlock, or death camas,

00:11:05.100 --> 00:11:07.410 align:middle line:10%
but there's just a
few poisonous plants,

00:11:07.410 --> 00:11:10.410 align:middle line:10%
and it's good to know
which ones are poisonous.

00:11:10.410 --> 00:11:14.610 align:middle line:84%
And I think before you
ingest any plant, whether it

00:11:14.610 --> 00:11:18.630 align:middle line:84%
be for food or a tea, that
you really need to be sure,

00:11:18.630 --> 00:11:21.930 align:middle line:84%
and make sure it's not collected
within a polluted area--

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:26.260 align:middle line:84%
usually at least 50 feet
away from a busy road,

00:11:26.260 --> 00:11:28.260 align:middle line:84%
and make sure you have
the right species and not

00:11:28.260 --> 00:11:29.890 align:middle line:90%
an endangered species.

00:11:29.890 --> 00:11:31.390 align:middle line:84%
So it takes some
level of learning,

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:33.681 align:middle line:84%
but what a valuable
thing to study.

00:11:33.681 --> 00:11:34.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, incredible.

00:11:34.680 --> 00:11:36.180 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: You feel
at home everywhere,

00:11:36.180 --> 00:11:38.400 align:middle line:84%
and you feel like, oh,
I recognize my friends.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:41.040 align:middle line:84%
You have lamb's quarter
here, or amaranth here,

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:44.940 align:middle line:84%
and then sometimes I
see homeless people,

00:11:44.940 --> 00:11:46.930 align:middle line:90%
and they're like, give me money.

00:11:46.930 --> 00:11:48.717 align:middle line:84%
And I sometimes say,
do you know you could

00:11:48.717 --> 00:11:49.800 align:middle line:90%
eat that right behind you?

00:11:49.800 --> 00:11:54.210 align:middle line:84%
We need never be hungry if
we know what is abounding.

00:11:54.210 --> 00:11:56.370 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is incredible.

00:11:56.370 --> 00:12:00.690 align:middle line:84%
So let's learn about our
gardens, about what we're

00:12:00.690 --> 00:12:01.800 align:middle line:90%
walking on.

00:12:01.800 --> 00:12:04.980 align:middle line:10%
First of all, you
say that a lawn--

00:12:04.980 --> 00:12:09.240 align:middle line:10%
we spend money to water
it, and then the mowers

00:12:09.240 --> 00:12:12.300 align:middle line:10%
come and use gas to mow
it, and then the trash bags

00:12:12.300 --> 00:12:13.110 align:middle line:10%
to fill the leaves.

00:12:13.110 --> 00:12:14.304 align:middle line:90%
Explain that cycle.

00:12:14.304 --> 00:12:15.720 align:middle line:84%
Let's really get
aware about this.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:17.190 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: It's crazy.

00:12:17.190 --> 00:12:24.060 align:middle line:84%
So I think that this really is
another type of bamboozlement.

00:12:24.060 --> 00:12:26.550 align:middle line:90%
Don't eat your lawn.

00:12:26.550 --> 00:12:29.100 align:middle line:90%
People will let the apples--

00:12:29.100 --> 00:12:31.410 align:middle line:84%
the organic apples
fall to the ground,

00:12:31.410 --> 00:12:34.530 align:middle line:84%
and then go to the store and
buy commercial apples that

00:12:34.530 --> 00:12:36.720 align:middle line:90%
are from another continent.

00:12:36.720 --> 00:12:40.350 align:middle line:10%
So we need to change that,
and I have an article online

00:12:40.350 --> 00:12:42.270 align:middle line:10%
that's called "Get
Off Your Grass

00:12:42.270 --> 00:12:43.920 align:middle line:10%
and Create an Edible Lawn."

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:45.280 align:middle line:90%
So it was in "Huffington Post."

00:12:45.280 --> 00:12:46.080 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great.

00:12:46.080 --> 00:12:48.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And it has lots
of ideas on edible lawns.

00:12:48.960 --> 00:12:50.700 align:middle line:84%
So another thing we
want to keep in mind

00:12:50.700 --> 00:12:56.910 align:middle line:84%
is that, when we do have
flowers in our yard, weeds,

00:12:56.910 --> 00:12:59.070 align:middle line:84%
this is food for
the pollinators,

00:12:59.070 --> 00:13:00.900 align:middle line:84%
for the bees, and
the butterflies,

00:13:00.900 --> 00:13:02.310 align:middle line:90%
and the hummingbirds.

00:13:02.310 --> 00:13:04.260 align:middle line:84%
So when we're just
growing grass,

00:13:04.260 --> 00:13:06.900 align:middle line:84%
there's no opportunity
for pollination,

00:13:06.900 --> 00:13:09.750 align:middle line:84%
and dandelions are actually
one of the first foods

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:11.400 align:middle line:90%
for the bees in the springtime.

00:13:11.400 --> 00:13:14.070 align:middle line:90%
So dandelions are not the enemy.

00:13:14.070 --> 00:13:16.980 align:middle line:84%
They are actually something
that was brought here

00:13:16.980 --> 00:13:19.350 align:middle line:84%
to this continent
by the pioneers.

00:13:19.350 --> 00:13:20.970 align:middle line:90%
They're native to Eurasia.

00:13:20.970 --> 00:13:22.920 align:middle line:84%
The pioneers put
fences around them

00:13:22.920 --> 00:13:25.680 align:middle line:84%
to keep the deer
and the rabbits out.

00:13:25.680 --> 00:13:28.960 align:middle line:84%
The dandelion leaves you
can eat in the springtime.

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:31.320 align:middle line:84%
They're tastiest
before they flower,

00:13:31.320 --> 00:13:34.260 align:middle line:84%
but they're high in
iron and potassium.

00:13:34.260 --> 00:13:37.560 align:middle line:84%
Dandelion leaves are
considered a supreme diuretic,

00:13:37.560 --> 00:13:40.990 align:middle line:84%
so they help to get rid of
excess fluid in your body.

00:13:40.990 --> 00:13:44.850 align:middle line:84%
Most chemical diuretics
deplete the body of potassium,

00:13:44.850 --> 00:13:48.570 align:middle line:84%
but dandelion leaves
give you potassium.

00:13:48.570 --> 00:13:52.050 align:middle line:84%
The dandelion flowers
are high in lutein, which

00:13:52.050 --> 00:13:53.340 align:middle line:90%
is really good for our eyes.

00:13:53.340 --> 00:13:55.260 align:middle line:84%
And yeah, you can go to
the health food store

00:13:55.260 --> 00:13:57.000 align:middle line:90%
and buy a bottle of lutein--

00:13:57.000 --> 00:14:03.000 align:middle line:84%
$20-- but we could be eating
the dandelion flowers.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:06.390 align:middle line:84%
I was just teaching in Iceland,
and the dandelions were really

00:14:06.390 --> 00:14:10.430 align:middle line:84%
long there, and we boiled
the stems like noodles.

00:14:10.430 --> 00:14:11.230 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:14:11.230 --> 00:14:12.646 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Like two
minutes, and then

00:14:12.646 --> 00:14:15.600 align:middle line:84%
sauteed them with
garlic and coconut oil,

00:14:15.600 --> 00:14:16.712 align:middle line:90%
and that was so yummy.

00:14:16.712 --> 00:14:17.670 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You're kidding.

00:14:17.670 --> 00:14:18.720 align:middle line:90%
Like a pad Thai.

00:14:18.720 --> 00:14:20.100 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Like a
pad Thai, and then

00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:23.190 align:middle line:84%
you can eat the dandelion
root, or roast the root

00:14:23.190 --> 00:14:24.840 align:middle line:90%
and make a coffee substitute.

00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:28.447 align:middle line:90%
So we have really been--

00:14:28.447 --> 00:14:29.280 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Conditioned.

00:14:29.280 --> 00:14:31.113 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Conditioned to
think that dandelions

00:14:31.113 --> 00:14:33.840 align:middle line:84%
are the enemy when they
are such a useful plant.

00:14:33.840 --> 00:14:35.920 align:middle line:84%
If I were going
to another planet,

00:14:35.920 --> 00:14:37.860 align:middle line:84%
I would want to have
dandelion seeds with me,

00:14:37.860 --> 00:14:39.480 align:middle line:90%
because they grow easily.

00:14:39.480 --> 00:14:42.720 align:middle line:84%
They're here a month before
you can even plant the garden.

00:14:42.720 --> 00:14:45.660 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And I think a yard
with dandelions is beautiful.

00:14:45.660 --> 00:14:48.840 align:middle line:10%
The little yellow flowers
that pop up-- it's gorgeous.

00:14:48.840 --> 00:14:53.610 align:middle line:84%
And as you say, our animals,
and our propagators of nature

00:14:53.610 --> 00:14:56.580 align:middle line:84%
are the ones that they go
to those flowers first.

00:14:56.580 --> 00:14:57.810 align:middle line:90%
We should learn from them.

00:14:57.810 --> 00:15:01.150 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And we need to change
these home owner restrictions.

00:15:01.150 --> 00:15:01.950 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Of course.

00:15:01.950 --> 00:15:05.070 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: These neighborhoods--
you can only grow grass,

00:15:05.070 --> 00:15:06.870 align:middle line:90%
and it can only be this tall.

00:15:06.870 --> 00:15:10.230 align:middle line:84%
Because that might have
been something fashionable,

00:15:10.230 --> 00:15:13.270 align:middle line:84%
but now we need to look
at, what is the future?

00:15:13.270 --> 00:15:16.380 align:middle line:84%
How can we conserve our
water and use it wisely?

00:15:16.380 --> 00:15:19.740 align:middle line:84%
And the dandelions actually
help aerate the soil,

00:15:19.740 --> 00:15:21.350 align:middle line:84%
so having dandelions
in your yard

00:15:21.350 --> 00:15:23.380 align:middle line:90%
is a good thing for the planet.

00:15:23.380 --> 00:15:26.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: What is the whole
concept of weed killer?

00:15:26.920 --> 00:15:28.570 align:middle line:90%
Where did that come from?

00:15:28.570 --> 00:15:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And now we're finally starting
to see how-- well, we we've

00:15:32.200 --> 00:15:34.719 align:middle line:84%
for a long time seen
how poisonous it is,

00:15:34.719 --> 00:15:37.010 align:middle line:84%
but it's finally starting to
get pulled off of shelves.

00:15:37.010 --> 00:15:41.470 align:middle line:10%
>>MARS: Well, I mean, after all,
we had Rachel Carson in 1962

00:15:41.470 --> 00:15:43.840 align:middle line:10%
in her book "Silent
Spring" warning us

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:46.210 align:middle line:10%
about the effects of
spraying pesticides,

00:15:46.210 --> 00:15:48.580 align:middle line:10%
and how it would kill the
insects, would kill the birds,

00:15:48.580 --> 00:15:51.047 align:middle line:10%
and that would increase
insect population,

00:15:51.047 --> 00:15:52.630 align:middle line:10%
because we'd no
longer have the birds,

00:15:52.630 --> 00:15:55.030 align:middle line:10%
and it would poison the water.

00:15:55.030 --> 00:15:56.680 align:middle line:90%
So this is not news.

00:15:56.680 --> 00:15:59.080 align:middle line:84%
We've known this,
but we are constantly

00:15:59.080 --> 00:16:01.210 align:middle line:84%
being bombarded with
media that makes

00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:05.560 align:middle line:84%
us think that having
edibles in your yard

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:08.320 align:middle line:84%
was a sign of not
being affluent enough.

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:10.540 align:middle line:84%
If you had a
useless yard, people

00:16:10.540 --> 00:16:12.220 align:middle line:84%
could drive by in
their carriages

00:16:12.220 --> 00:16:15.820 align:middle line:90%
and say they must be so rich.

00:16:15.820 --> 00:16:20.370 align:middle line:84%
And so it became associated
with being maybe a lower class,

00:16:20.370 --> 00:16:22.140 align:middle line:84%
but now we have to
think about, how

00:16:22.140 --> 00:16:24.430 align:middle line:84%
are we going to feed all
the people on the planet?

00:16:24.430 --> 00:16:28.060 align:middle line:84%
And having edible
lawns is a great start.

00:16:28.060 --> 00:16:28.960 align:middle line:90%
Use less gas.

00:16:28.960 --> 00:16:30.530 align:middle line:90%
Go pick your salad in your yard.

00:16:30.530 --> 00:16:31.330 align:middle line:90%
It's fresher.

00:16:31.330 --> 00:16:32.470 align:middle line:90%
It's free.

00:16:32.470 --> 00:16:34.420 align:middle line:84%
How many of us are
thinking about how can we

00:16:34.420 --> 00:16:38.200 align:middle line:84%
stretch our food dollars
to make them go longer?

00:16:38.200 --> 00:16:41.770 align:middle line:84%
And most of the so-called weeds
that come up in our garden

00:16:41.770 --> 00:16:45.550 align:middle line:84%
are actually the ancestors
of cultivated plants.

00:16:45.550 --> 00:16:47.080 align:middle line:84%
You might hate
thistles, but they're

00:16:47.080 --> 00:16:49.000 align:middle line:90%
the ancestors of artichokes.

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:51.190 align:middle line:84%
You might not
appreciate chicory,

00:16:51.190 --> 00:16:55.900 align:middle line:84%
but they're the ancestors
of endive and escarole.

00:16:55.900 --> 00:16:59.050 align:middle line:10%
Lamb's quarter is wild spinach.

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:02.340 align:middle line:10%
So why would we pull
that up out of the yard?

00:17:02.340 --> 00:17:03.270 align:middle line:90%
I'm just going--

00:17:03.270 --> 00:17:04.561 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: This is lamb's quarter?

00:17:04.561 --> 00:17:06.579 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yeah, this is
lamb's quarter right here.

00:17:06.579 --> 00:17:09.550 align:middle line:84%
It's wild spinach, and
people will work really hard

00:17:09.550 --> 00:17:13.030 align:middle line:84%
in their garden, in
the hot sun, sweating,

00:17:13.030 --> 00:17:15.760 align:middle line:84%
to get rid of this
plant, when it's

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:17.890 align:middle line:90%
more nutritious than spinach.

00:17:17.890 --> 00:17:20.200 align:middle line:84%
And it's offering
itself for free.

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:24.220 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: This is what makes
everything so fragrant.

00:17:24.220 --> 00:17:27.819 align:middle line:84%
The flowers-- your wildflowers
growing around makes spring

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:28.930 align:middle line:90%
smell like spring.

00:17:28.930 --> 00:17:33.020 align:middle line:84%
It's a wonderful--
wow, that's great.

00:17:33.020 --> 00:17:34.990 align:middle line:90%
It reminds me of spring.

00:17:34.990 --> 00:17:37.610 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: So really it's time.

00:17:37.610 --> 00:17:40.150 align:middle line:84%
We hear about raising
consciousness.

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:42.250 align:middle line:84%
That's what we
want to do, and so

00:17:42.250 --> 00:17:44.740 align:middle line:84%
if we start with our
own little plot of land,

00:17:44.740 --> 00:17:47.560 align:middle line:84%
whether it's our
balcony, or our porch,

00:17:47.560 --> 00:17:50.620 align:middle line:84%
or the front yard, or the
backyard, or the window sill,

00:17:50.620 --> 00:17:52.380 align:middle line:90%
but we can all grow something.

00:17:52.380 --> 00:17:55.180 align:middle line:84%
And if you want to get
your kids to eat healthier,

00:17:55.180 --> 00:17:58.550 align:middle line:84%
you get them to participate
in that miracle of growing

00:17:58.550 --> 00:17:59.350 align:middle line:90%
something.

00:17:59.350 --> 00:18:01.130 align:middle line:84%
And if they didn't
like carrots before,

00:18:01.130 --> 00:18:03.380 align:middle line:84%
they're probably going to
like it once they grow them.

00:18:03.380 --> 00:18:04.810 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Once they
grow them, yes.

00:18:04.810 --> 00:18:07.690 align:middle line:84%
I was growing kale for a long
time, because I love kale,

00:18:07.690 --> 00:18:10.480 align:middle line:84%
but my gophers liked
it more than me.

00:18:10.480 --> 00:18:11.650 align:middle line:90%
They got to it first.

00:18:11.650 --> 00:18:15.850 align:middle line:84%
How do you suggest natural
pest control like that?

00:18:15.850 --> 00:18:18.495 align:middle line:90%
Divert them to something else?

00:18:18.495 --> 00:18:22.030 align:middle line:10%
>>MARS: Well, I think that
there is, at least for moles,

00:18:22.030 --> 00:18:24.040 align:middle line:10%
and maybe they're
similar to gophers,

00:18:24.040 --> 00:18:28.210 align:middle line:10%
but putting castor bean
seeds in the ground

00:18:28.210 --> 00:18:31.390 align:middle line:10%
is said to deter them.

00:18:31.390 --> 00:18:34.000 align:middle line:84%
I don't have them here,
so it's been a long time

00:18:34.000 --> 00:18:36.040 align:middle line:84%
since I've had
that, but I remember

00:18:36.040 --> 00:18:37.840 align:middle line:84%
that we would put
castor bean seeds

00:18:37.840 --> 00:18:39.760 align:middle line:84%
and that somehow that
was diverting them.

00:18:39.760 --> 00:18:42.287 align:middle line:84%
Also planting enough so
there's enough for everybody.

00:18:42.287 --> 00:18:43.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's good.

00:18:43.120 --> 00:18:46.480 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I also think
you can do the Jedi

00:18:46.480 --> 00:18:52.480 align:middle line:84%
mind meld and let them know
we're not going to bother you.

00:18:52.480 --> 00:18:55.450 align:middle line:84%
This is yours, and we want a
certain amount for ourselves,

00:18:55.450 --> 00:18:57.730 align:middle line:90%
and we can all coexist.

00:18:57.730 --> 00:19:01.690 align:middle line:84%
And I do think that there
are ways of communicating.

00:19:01.690 --> 00:19:03.730 align:middle line:90%
Maybe playing music.

00:19:03.730 --> 00:19:05.700 align:middle line:84%
Maybe planting foods
that they don't like,

00:19:05.700 --> 00:19:08.917 align:middle line:84%
like garlic or onions
might deter them.

00:19:08.917 --> 00:19:11.500 align:middle line:84%
But I think the other thing is
just plant so much that there's

00:19:11.500 --> 00:19:13.250 align:middle line:90%
enough for everybody.

00:19:13.250 --> 00:19:15.160 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Natural pest
control, and that's

00:19:15.160 --> 00:19:17.576 align:middle line:84%
what I was getting at-- is
there's a lot of different ways

00:19:17.576 --> 00:19:18.400 align:middle line:90%
to do it.

00:19:18.400 --> 00:19:20.570 align:middle line:84%
You make these great
recipes, and you have

00:19:20.570 --> 00:19:22.260 align:middle line:90%
all sorts of fantastic videos.

00:19:22.260 --> 00:19:23.060 align:middle line:90%
I chose this one.

00:19:23.060 --> 00:19:24.184 align:middle line:90%
It's called the fruit whip.

00:19:24.184 --> 00:19:25.870 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:19:25.870 --> 00:19:27.907 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Hi, welcome to
my raw-some kitchen.

00:19:27.907 --> 00:19:29.740 align:middle line:84%
I'm Brigitte Mars, and
I'm going to show you

00:19:29.740 --> 00:19:33.260 align:middle line:84%
how to make a simple,
antioxidant rich--

00:19:33.260 --> 00:19:34.930 align:middle line:84%
I call it a fruit
whip, and it's going

00:19:34.930 --> 00:19:37.900 align:middle line:84%
to give you all the
colors of the rainbow

00:19:37.900 --> 00:19:40.400 align:middle line:90%
and be super healthy, too.

00:19:40.400 --> 00:19:43.190 align:middle line:84%
I used to worry about how
many calories avocados were,

00:19:43.190 --> 00:19:46.530 align:middle line:84%
but avocados also
contain lecithin,

00:19:46.530 --> 00:19:51.490 align:middle line:84%
and they also contain lipase, an
enzyme to help you digest fats.

00:19:51.490 --> 00:19:55.390 align:middle line:84%
And, of course, oranges are
a great source of vitamin C.

00:19:55.390 --> 00:19:58.240 align:middle line:84%
And then we are going
to add some weeds.

00:19:58.240 --> 00:20:02.200 align:middle line:84%
So hopefully you do not
spray herbicides in your yard

00:20:02.200 --> 00:20:05.530 align:middle line:84%
or never, never in
your garden, but this

00:20:05.530 --> 00:20:07.780 align:middle line:84%
is something you to with
some of the extra greens

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:09.580 align:middle line:90%
that offer themselves freely.

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:13.000 align:middle line:84%
We have lemon balm here,
Melissa officinalis--

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:16.140 align:middle line:84%
wonderful for
helping one to focus.

00:20:16.140 --> 00:20:20.040 align:middle line:84%
Lemon balm is said to be
a remedy for depression.

00:20:20.040 --> 00:20:24.710 align:middle line:84%
We have some cleavers, which
are very lymphatic cleansing.

00:20:24.710 --> 00:20:29.210 align:middle line:84%
We have an herb known
as stinging nettle,

00:20:29.210 --> 00:20:32.270 align:middle line:84%
and you might say, well, don't
stinging nettles sting you?

00:20:32.270 --> 00:20:37.100 align:middle line:84%
They do, but if you blend them,
puree them, cook them, or dry

00:20:37.100 --> 00:20:39.470 align:middle line:90%
them, they lose their sting.

00:20:39.470 --> 00:20:42.590 align:middle line:84%
And the infamous
dandelion leaf--

00:20:42.590 --> 00:20:45.620 align:middle line:84%
dandelion leaves are
high in potassium,

00:20:45.620 --> 00:20:47.630 align:middle line:90%
and they are diuretic.

00:20:47.630 --> 00:20:50.450 align:middle line:84%
They're high in iron
and beta carotene,

00:20:50.450 --> 00:20:51.980 align:middle line:90%
and they do not kill the grass.

00:20:51.980 --> 00:20:54.580 align:middle line:84%
They actually help
aerate the soil.

00:20:54.580 --> 00:20:57.600 align:middle line:10%
And lamb's quarter is
actually wild spinach--

00:20:57.600 --> 00:20:59.330 align:middle line:10%
chenopodium album.

00:20:59.330 --> 00:21:01.539 align:middle line:84%
It's even more
nutritious than spinach.

00:21:01.539 --> 00:21:03.080 align:middle line:84%
And I have just a
little bit of mint.

00:21:03.080 --> 00:21:06.500 align:middle line:90%
That'll make it taste great.

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:09.650 align:middle line:84%
So learn about the weeds
that grow in your yard.

00:21:09.650 --> 00:21:12.440 align:middle line:84%
Not only are they fresh,
because all these plants were

00:21:12.440 --> 00:21:16.330 align:middle line:84%
growing just about two minutes
ago, they're also free.

00:21:16.330 --> 00:21:20.270 align:middle line:10%
And this is a yellow dock,
rumex crispus, also very high

00:21:20.270 --> 00:21:23.120 align:middle line:10%
in vitamin C and iron.

00:21:23.120 --> 00:21:27.410 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to add maybe a couple
of tablespoons of water just

00:21:27.410 --> 00:21:31.370 align:middle line:84%
to help the blender
be a little happier,

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:34.370 align:middle line:84%
and turn my new
Waring blender on.

00:21:34.370 --> 00:21:47.340 align:middle line:90%


00:21:47.340 --> 00:21:49.650 align:middle line:90%
And voila.

00:21:49.650 --> 00:21:51.390 align:middle line:90%
You serve this in a bowl.

00:21:51.390 --> 00:21:55.800 align:middle line:84%
You can decorate it with
some edible flowers.

00:21:55.800 --> 00:21:59.520 align:middle line:84%
I have here a pansy, but
you could add some raw cacao

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:02.250 align:middle line:90%
nibs, goji berries, some nuts.

00:22:02.250 --> 00:22:05.040 align:middle line:84%
And this is so delicious
it'll make you feel

00:22:05.040 --> 00:22:07.260 align:middle line:90%
like a superhuman all day long.

00:22:07.260 --> 00:22:11.740 align:middle line:84%
Thanks for joining me, Brigitte
Mars, in the raw-some kitchen.

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:13.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: First of all,
you said in there

00:22:13.380 --> 00:22:14.880 align:middle line:84%
