So a lot of herbal teas would
be even more medicinal if we

00:29:10.530 --> 00:29:12.750 align:middle line:90%
were to let them steep longer--

00:29:12.750 --> 00:29:16.500 align:middle line:84%
20 minutes minimum, but
I steep a lot of my herbs

00:29:16.500 --> 00:29:18.120 align:middle line:90%
even overnight.

00:29:18.120 --> 00:29:19.500 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Does it open it up more?

00:29:19.500 --> 00:29:21.700 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yes, you get
more minerals from it.

00:29:21.700 --> 00:29:25.290 align:middle line:84%
So there's something called
an overnight infusion, where

00:29:25.290 --> 00:29:29.640 align:middle line:84%
you put your-- maybe an inch
of dried herb in a Ball jar

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:32.530 align:middle line:84%
and then cover it to
the top with hot water.

00:29:32.530 --> 00:29:33.510 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: A Ball jar?

00:29:33.510 --> 00:29:34.310 align:middle line:90%
What's a--

00:29:34.310 --> 00:29:37.260 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: A canning jar, a
Mason jar, any of those jars.

00:29:37.260 --> 00:29:39.210 align:middle line:84%
Put the lid on, and
let it sit overnight,

00:29:39.210 --> 00:29:42.090 align:middle line:84%
and then the color
is even more vibrant,

00:29:42.090 --> 00:29:44.600 align:middle line:84%
but, again, company comes
over, you don't say,

00:29:44.600 --> 00:29:45.600 align:middle line:90%
can you spend the night?

00:29:45.600 --> 00:29:46.840 align:middle line:90%
I'm going to make us some tea.

00:29:46.840 --> 00:29:48.131 align:middle line:90%
Are you leaving in the morning?

00:29:48.131 --> 00:29:50.250 align:middle line:84%
That's not going to be
everyone who comes over.

00:29:50.250 --> 00:29:52.410 align:middle line:84%
So sometimes it's
company's coming.

00:29:52.410 --> 00:29:55.260 align:middle line:84%
Let's have a cup of
tea in 10 minutes.

00:29:55.260 --> 00:29:57.240 align:middle line:84%
But I also like the
idea of supporting

00:29:57.240 --> 00:30:02.550 align:middle line:84%
local her stores that have
herbs in a bigger cut.

00:30:02.550 --> 00:30:03.360 align:middle line:90%
Chefs know this.

00:30:03.360 --> 00:30:07.860 align:middle line:84%
When we are using a culinary
herb like cardamom or cumin,

00:30:07.860 --> 00:30:10.770 align:middle line:84%
if we want to be
an amazing chef,

00:30:10.770 --> 00:30:14.250 align:middle line:84%
we're going to buy the whole
seed and grind it up fresh.

00:30:14.250 --> 00:30:17.460 align:middle line:84%
If you buy the powder
cumin or cardamom that

00:30:17.460 --> 00:30:20.280 align:middle line:84%
was ground up two
years ago, maybe

00:30:20.280 --> 00:30:22.500 align:middle line:84%
sitting in a spice
jar in your cupboard,

00:30:22.500 --> 00:30:26.340 align:middle line:84%
the flavor is not going to be as
intense, because essential oils

00:30:26.340 --> 00:30:28.340 align:middle line:90%
evaporate more quickly.

00:30:28.340 --> 00:30:30.610 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you recommend
grinding them in the--

00:30:30.610 --> 00:30:31.410 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Yes.

00:30:31.410 --> 00:30:33.700 align:middle line:84%
I have a little
mortar and pestle.

00:30:33.700 --> 00:30:34.500 align:middle line:90%
I like that.

00:30:34.500 --> 00:30:37.870 align:middle line:84%
That's an ancient
tool, the mortar

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:40.080 align:middle line:84%
is said to symbolize
the feminine,

00:30:40.080 --> 00:30:42.630 align:middle line:90%
and the pestle is the masculine.

00:30:42.630 --> 00:30:45.690 align:middle line:84%
And my grandchildren love
the story of baba yaga.

00:30:45.690 --> 00:30:47.730 align:middle line:84%
She's like this
Russian witch, and she

00:30:47.730 --> 00:30:51.040 align:middle line:84%
flies in a mortar and pestle,
and she uses it to steer.

00:30:51.040 --> 00:30:53.520 align:middle line:84%
But so yes, I have
a mortar and pestle,

00:30:53.520 --> 00:30:55.559 align:middle line:90%
but you could use your blender.

00:30:55.559 --> 00:30:56.850 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I like that way better.

00:30:56.850 --> 00:30:57.450 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Or a little
coffee grinder.

00:30:57.450 --> 00:30:58.866 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Because
the stone probably

00:30:58.866 --> 00:31:02.760 align:middle line:10%
also helps release
all those great aromas

00:31:02.760 --> 00:31:05.040 align:middle line:10%
and break up the hulls.

00:31:05.040 --> 00:31:06.960 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: It does, and
I also feel like it's

00:31:06.960 --> 00:31:10.440 align:middle line:84%
putting your intention into it,
and that's part of making food,

00:31:10.440 --> 00:31:11.340 align:middle line:90%
too.

00:31:11.340 --> 00:31:13.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Tell me
about organic foods.

00:31:13.380 --> 00:31:16.860 align:middle line:84%
Why are they so
expensive in the markets?

00:31:16.860 --> 00:31:21.259 align:middle line:84%
How can we really eat organic
without it being so ridiculous?

00:31:21.259 --> 00:31:22.800 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, we
want to keep in mind

00:31:22.800 --> 00:31:26.515 align:middle line:84%
that the cost of organic
foods is coming down as it's

00:31:26.515 --> 00:31:27.515 align:middle line:90%
becoming more available.

00:31:27.515 --> 00:31:28.315 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Good.

00:31:28.315 --> 00:31:31.320 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: But initially there
were just organic apples

00:31:31.320 --> 00:31:32.340 align:middle line:90%
and organic carrots.

00:31:32.340 --> 00:31:36.030 align:middle line:84%
That's all you could buy in
the '60s, and now there's--

00:31:36.030 --> 00:31:38.220 align:middle line:84%
almost everything
you can get organic,

00:31:38.220 --> 00:31:41.230 align:middle line:84%
but they're usually
done on a smaller scale,

00:31:41.230 --> 00:31:43.657 align:middle line:90%
so the farms are not as large.

00:31:43.657 --> 00:31:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But that's
good because you're

00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:46.680 align:middle line:90%
supporting smaller farms.

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:48.630 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: But if we
support it, it's

00:31:48.630 --> 00:31:50.800 align:middle line:90%
going to become more available.

00:31:50.800 --> 00:31:54.180 align:middle line:84%
But the other thing is grow
your own organic garden.

00:31:54.180 --> 00:31:55.920 align:middle line:84%
Farmer's markets
are also good things

00:31:55.920 --> 00:32:01.080 align:middle line:84%
to support to also think
about buying things in season.

00:32:01.080 --> 00:32:03.600 align:middle line:84%
You're going to buy organic
peaches when they're

00:32:03.600 --> 00:32:05.730 align:middle line:84%
in season in your
state, and I'm going

00:32:05.730 --> 00:32:08.250 align:middle line:84%
to wait for when they're
in season in my state,

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:12.560 align:middle line:84%
rather than I've got to have
them in May or something

00:32:12.560 --> 00:32:14.330 align:middle line:90%
shipped from another continent.

00:32:14.330 --> 00:32:18.230 align:middle line:84%
So I think if we pay
attention to not only eating

00:32:18.230 --> 00:32:21.200 align:middle line:90%
more local, but also seasonal--

00:32:21.200 --> 00:32:23.060 align:middle line:84%
I was in Switzerland,
and this restaurant

00:32:23.060 --> 00:32:24.870 align:middle line:90%
had 12 things on the menu.

00:32:24.870 --> 00:32:25.670 align:middle line:90%
It was early May.

00:32:25.670 --> 00:32:27.980 align:middle line:84%
They had asparagus
soup, asparagus salad,

00:32:27.980 --> 00:32:30.650 align:middle line:84%
asparagus souffle,
asparagus quiche,

00:32:30.650 --> 00:32:32.070 align:middle line:90%
because that was in season.

00:32:32.070 --> 00:32:35.690 align:middle line:84%
And I think that we might
want to think about looking

00:32:35.690 --> 00:32:38.090 align:middle line:90%
at what is happening right now.

00:32:38.090 --> 00:32:40.910 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: In the season that
you're in wherever you are.

00:32:40.910 --> 00:32:44.780 align:middle line:84%
What are some good starter
herbs to start your garden with?

00:32:44.780 --> 00:32:47.180 align:middle line:90%
Some hardy starter herbs.

00:32:47.180 --> 00:32:49.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, a couple
that I think of--

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:50.748 align:middle line:84%
sometimes people are
worried that they're

00:32:50.748 --> 00:32:53.330 align:middle line:84%
going to take over, but
I say let them take over.

00:32:53.330 --> 00:32:54.860 align:middle line:90%
They're wonderful for the bees.

00:32:54.860 --> 00:32:56.680 align:middle line:10%
Lemon balm is a great one--

00:32:56.680 --> 00:32:58.899 align:middle line:10%
Melissa officinalis.

00:32:58.899 --> 00:33:00.440 align:middle line:10%
So if you know
someone named Melissa,

00:33:00.440 --> 00:33:03.630 align:middle line:10%
you could say, oh, your
name means honey leaf.

00:33:03.630 --> 00:33:06.530 align:middle line:84%
And officinalis
means the official.

00:33:06.530 --> 00:33:08.850 align:middle line:90%
So lemon balm tastes good.

00:33:08.850 --> 00:33:09.650 align:middle line:90%
It's lemony.

00:33:09.650 --> 00:33:11.840 align:middle line:84%
It's a member of
the mint family.

00:33:11.840 --> 00:33:14.740 align:middle line:84%
It has long been considered
an antidepressant.

00:33:14.740 --> 00:33:15.540 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:33:15.540 --> 00:33:17.081 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: You could
crush it up, put it

00:33:17.081 --> 00:33:19.490 align:middle line:84%
in your water bottle
or your water carafe.

00:33:19.490 --> 00:33:21.920 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It's a
super sturdy leaf.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:25.790 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: It is one of the
favorite foods of honeybees.

00:33:25.790 --> 00:33:27.320 align:middle line:84%
It's also really
good for the liver,

00:33:27.320 --> 00:33:31.670 align:middle line:84%
and it's also antiviral against
cold, and flu, and even herpes

00:33:31.670 --> 00:33:32.870 align:middle line:90%
virus.

00:33:32.870 --> 00:33:36.230 align:middle line:84%
It's used a lot in European
medicine for topical creams,

00:33:36.230 --> 00:33:41.150 align:middle line:84%
for even things like shingles
and cold sore outbreaks.

00:33:41.150 --> 00:33:42.410 align:middle line:90%
The other one is mint.

00:33:42.410 --> 00:33:43.820 align:middle line:90%
Both of these are perennials.

00:33:43.820 --> 00:33:46.570 align:middle line:84%
They'll come back
year after year.

00:33:46.570 --> 00:33:48.950 align:middle line:90%
Mint-- we think of mint.

00:33:48.950 --> 00:33:51.950 align:middle line:84%
We can only use it as tea, but
if you have an abundance of it,

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:56.060 align:middle line:84%
cut it, dry it in a paper bag,
give it to all your friends

00:33:56.060 --> 00:33:57.670 align:middle line:90%
for winter tea.

00:33:57.670 --> 00:34:00.470 align:middle line:84%
It makes a nice
cooling summer bath.

00:34:00.470 --> 00:34:01.600 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: How do you dry it?

00:34:01.600 --> 00:34:04.220 align:middle line:84%
I have an out-of-control
mint plant.

00:34:04.220 --> 00:34:08.350 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, just cut it,
put it in a paper bag loosely,

00:34:08.350 --> 00:34:10.969 align:middle line:84%
and ideally you want to cut it
when the plant is just starting

00:34:10.969 --> 00:34:14.929 align:middle line:84%
to flower early in the day, not
when it's all tired and wilty

00:34:14.929 --> 00:34:17.570 align:middle line:90%
at the end of a hot day.

00:34:17.570 --> 00:34:20.420 align:middle line:84%
And I usually just dry
them in a warm room.

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:23.719 align:middle line:84%
So it could be the top floor,
or some people dry them

00:34:23.719 --> 00:34:25.100 align:middle line:90%
in the backseat of the car.

00:34:25.100 --> 00:34:27.469 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to
dry them in the sun.

00:34:27.469 --> 00:34:30.440 align:middle line:84%
Shade is better, because the sun
will cause the essential oils

00:34:30.440 --> 00:34:31.460 align:middle line:90%
to evaporate.

00:34:31.460 --> 00:34:31.760 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And burn.

00:34:31.760 --> 00:34:34.010 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I know we've all
seen the pioneer movies where

00:34:34.010 --> 00:34:35.630 align:middle line:84%
they're hanging
from the rafters,

00:34:35.630 --> 00:34:38.239 align:middle line:84%
and you can do that, too,
but once they are dry,

00:34:38.239 --> 00:34:40.670 align:middle line:84%
you want to store
them in a glass jar,

00:34:40.670 --> 00:34:43.010 align:middle line:84%
or come the time you're
about to use them,

00:34:43.010 --> 00:34:46.320 align:middle line:84%
they'll have spider webs on
them and stuff like that.

00:34:46.320 --> 00:34:48.350 align:middle line:90%
But it's very easy to dry herbs.

00:34:48.350 --> 00:34:52.010 align:middle line:84%
People have been drying
herbs for thousands of years,

00:34:52.010 --> 00:34:55.370 align:middle line:84%
and a loose paper
bag works great.

00:34:55.370 --> 00:34:56.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wonderful.

00:34:56.330 --> 00:35:00.330 align:middle line:84%
Another tip I'd love to know
is, when you do get produce,

00:35:00.330 --> 00:35:02.780 align:middle line:84%
do you not put it
in the refrigerator?

00:35:02.780 --> 00:35:06.380 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Some things need to be
refrigerated more than others,

00:35:06.380 --> 00:35:09.544 align:middle line:84%
but I think we over
refrigerate things.

00:35:09.544 --> 00:35:11.210 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: I know tomatoes
are not supposed

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:11.990 align:middle line:90%
to go in the refrigerator.

00:35:11.990 --> 00:35:13.448 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yeah, and
a lot of things--

00:35:13.448 --> 00:35:15.230 align:middle line:84%
it's sometimes
appropriate to look at,

00:35:15.230 --> 00:35:18.027 align:middle line:84%
was it refrigerated
at the store?

00:35:18.027 --> 00:35:20.360 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: But no, if you get
it from the farmer's market--

00:35:20.360 --> 00:35:22.490 align:middle line:90%
like avocados should stay out.

00:35:22.490 --> 00:35:25.040 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: But once they're ripe,
put them in the refrigerator,

00:35:25.040 --> 00:35:26.940 align:middle line:90%
or they will continue to ripen.

00:35:26.940 --> 00:35:30.542 align:middle line:84%
So once your peaches are ripe,
put them in the refrigerator,

00:35:30.542 --> 00:35:32.250 align:middle line:84%
and they'll still be
good for a few days.

00:35:32.250 --> 00:35:33.800 align:middle line:84%
But if you just
let them sit there,

00:35:33.800 --> 00:35:35.820 align:middle line:84%
they will get
overripe very quickly.

00:35:35.820 --> 00:35:36.620 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Fast.

00:35:36.620 --> 00:35:37.710 align:middle line:90%
Same with tomatoes.

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:40.545 align:middle line:90%
And lemons are pretty good.

00:35:40.545 --> 00:35:42.920 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Lemons, potatoes you
don't usually need to ripen,

00:35:42.920 --> 00:35:47.810 align:middle line:84%
but, again, they're usually
not refrigerated at the store.

00:35:47.810 --> 00:35:49.865 align:middle line:84%
And I've been using
a solar oven lately.

00:35:49.865 --> 00:35:50.914 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: What's that?

00:35:50.914 --> 00:35:52.580 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I bought this
little solar oven.

00:35:52.580 --> 00:35:55.730 align:middle line:84%
I got them for everybody in
my family for the holidays,

00:35:55.730 --> 00:35:58.910 align:middle line:84%
and it's a little
tube with reflectors,

00:35:58.910 --> 00:36:01.580 align:middle line:84%
and I've been baking
little potatoes in the sun,

00:36:01.580 --> 00:36:03.620 align:middle line:90%
or cauliflower in the sun.

00:36:03.620 --> 00:36:06.257 align:middle line:84%
And it's a small step to
being more sustainable.

00:36:06.257 --> 00:36:07.090 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: I love that.

00:36:07.090 --> 00:36:09.500 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And I don't have
solar panels on my house

00:36:09.500 --> 00:36:11.390 align:middle line:84%
because I live in a
condo, and hopefully

00:36:11.390 --> 00:36:13.880 align:middle line:84%
that will come someday,
but if we could just

00:36:13.880 --> 00:36:16.870 align:middle line:84%
take some small steps
to going more solar,

00:36:16.870 --> 00:36:17.865 align:middle line:90%
a solar oven is great.

00:36:17.865 --> 00:36:19.490 align:middle line:84%
And then you don't
heat your kitchen up

00:36:19.490 --> 00:36:20.840 align:middle line:90%
when the weather's hot.

00:36:20.840 --> 00:36:22.370 align:middle line:90%
I love to use a lot of raw food.

00:36:22.370 --> 00:36:24.170 align:middle line:84%
I do eat a high
percentage of raw food,

00:36:24.170 --> 00:36:27.190 align:middle line:84%
but the idea that we could
be cooking with the sun--

00:36:27.190 --> 00:36:27.990 align:middle line:90%
it's amazing.

00:36:27.990 --> 00:36:28.880 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is great.

00:36:28.880 --> 00:36:30.379 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: It feels
like it's putting--

00:36:30.379 --> 00:36:31.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Just it's that long?

00:36:31.820 --> 00:36:32.640 align:middle line:90%
It's not that long?

00:36:32.640 --> 00:36:33.598 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: It's that long.

00:36:33.598 --> 00:36:34.590 align:middle line:90%
It's like a long tube.

00:36:34.590 --> 00:36:36.050 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And you could
put potatoes and--

00:36:36.050 --> 00:36:36.850 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Potatoes.

00:36:36.850 --> 00:36:37.770 align:middle line:90%
I've done cauliflower.

00:36:37.770 --> 00:36:39.645 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Does it work
like a dehydrator or no?

00:36:39.645 --> 00:36:41.810 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: No, it
makes things juicy.

00:36:41.810 --> 00:36:43.910 align:middle line:10%
It steams.

00:36:43.910 --> 00:36:45.770 align:middle line:84%
Although if you left
things in it too long,

00:36:45.770 --> 00:36:47.960 align:middle line:84%
it probably would dehydrate
things eventually,

00:36:47.960 --> 00:36:49.456 align:middle line:90%
but it's not a dehydrator.

00:36:49.456 --> 00:36:51.080 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: If you don't
have a dehydrator,

00:36:51.080 --> 00:36:53.360 align:middle line:90%
can you also use an oven?

00:36:53.360 --> 00:36:55.400 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, an oven
doesn't have a fan

00:36:55.400 --> 00:36:58.580 align:middle line:90%
to blow the moisture out.

00:36:58.580 --> 00:37:00.410 align:middle line:90%
So I just want to share this.

00:37:00.410 --> 00:37:03.210 align:middle line:84%
When I lived in the teepee in
the Ozarks, for most of it,

00:37:03.210 --> 00:37:05.130 align:middle line:90%
we didn't have electricity.

00:37:05.130 --> 00:37:08.234 align:middle line:84%
And we wanted to dehydrate
food for the winter,

00:37:08.234 --> 00:37:10.150 align:middle line:84%
because what are we going
to eat in the winter

00:37:10.150 --> 00:37:12.650 align:middle line:84%
when there's snow
covering the ground?

00:37:12.650 --> 00:37:16.360 align:middle line:84%
So for some reason, we had a
trampoline on the property,

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:19.297 align:middle line:84%
and I would lay sliced peaches,
and blackberries, and things--

00:37:19.297 --> 00:37:20.380 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: On the trampoline.

00:37:20.380 --> 00:37:21.550 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: On the trampoline.

00:37:21.550 --> 00:37:25.630 align:middle line:84%
I'd cover it with lace
to repel the flies

00:37:25.630 --> 00:37:27.080 align:middle line:90%
so they couldn't land on it.

00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:29.230 align:middle line:84%
And then in many
parts of the country,

00:37:29.230 --> 00:37:32.110 align:middle line:84%
the dew comes, and everything
gets really moist at night.

00:37:32.110 --> 00:37:34.507 align:middle line:84%
So at night, I would
bring it back inside.

00:37:34.507 --> 00:37:35.840 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That's a brilliant idea.

00:37:35.840 --> 00:37:37.000 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And then I
would take it back out,

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:38.583 align:middle line:84%
and they'd be dry
in a couple of days.

00:37:38.583 --> 00:37:40.990 align:middle line:84%
And then when they're dry,
you label them and put them

00:37:40.990 --> 00:37:44.290 align:middle line:84%
in a glass jar, and you
have food for the winter.

00:37:44.290 --> 00:37:46.000 align:middle line:90%
And it's so easy.

00:37:46.000 --> 00:37:47.982 align:middle line:84%
Let's say you want
to make an apple pie.

00:37:47.982 --> 00:37:49.690 align:middle line:84%
You just soak it in
water, and now you've

00:37:49.690 --> 00:37:52.440 align:middle line:84%
got nice, juicy,
moist apples again.

00:37:52.440 --> 00:37:53.440 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: That is amazing.

00:37:53.440 --> 00:37:56.920 align:middle line:84%
You were that creative
when you were a teenager.

00:37:56.920 --> 00:37:59.185 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Necessity is
the mother of invention.

00:37:59.185 --> 00:38:01.060 align:middle line:84%
It's like, yeah, how
are we going to do this?

00:38:01.060 --> 00:38:05.140 align:middle line:84%
And I really held in
high esteem the people

00:38:05.140 --> 00:38:09.010 align:middle line:84%
that had lived on this
continent before we got here.

00:38:09.010 --> 00:38:14.140 align:middle line:84%
They didn't go to the
store or have a dehydrator.

00:38:14.140 --> 00:38:15.640 align:middle line:90%
People smoked things.

00:38:15.640 --> 00:38:17.390 align:middle line:90%
They used the sun energy.

00:38:17.390 --> 00:38:19.210 align:middle line:90%
They used the wind.

00:38:19.210 --> 00:38:21.100 align:middle line:84%
And I think we're
going to need to start

00:38:21.100 --> 00:38:25.660 align:middle line:84%
doing that more to save energy,
and also to be more empowered,

00:38:25.660 --> 00:38:29.260 align:middle line:84%
and to unplug more from
corporate companies that

00:38:29.260 --> 00:38:31.070 align:middle line:90%
are polluting our planet.

00:38:31.070 --> 00:38:33.310 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And not to
support that level.

00:38:33.310 --> 00:38:36.880 align:middle line:84%
This is Brigitte on a nature
walk, and look what she finds.

00:38:36.880 --> 00:38:37.970 align:middle line:90%
Take a look.

00:38:37.970 --> 00:38:39.050 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Welcome.

00:38:39.050 --> 00:38:43.420 align:middle line:10%
I'm Brigitte Mars, and I'm here
on the beautiful campus of Gaia

00:38:43.420 --> 00:38:45.520 align:middle line:10%
outside Boulder, Colorado.

00:38:45.520 --> 00:38:48.892 align:middle line:10%
And there are so many plants
just within a few yards.

00:38:48.892 --> 00:38:51.100 align:middle line:84%
So we're going to just take
a little walk around here

00:38:51.100 --> 00:38:52.960 align:middle line:84%
and see how you
might incorporate

00:38:52.960 --> 00:38:55.960 align:middle line:84%
some of these wild
plants into your life.

00:38:55.960 --> 00:38:58.720 align:middle line:90%
So here we go.

00:38:58.720 --> 00:39:02.860 align:middle line:84%
One plant that most people
don't appreciate is the thistle.

00:39:02.860 --> 00:39:05.170 align:middle line:84%
There's many, many
varieties of thistle.

00:39:05.170 --> 00:39:07.870 align:middle line:84%
Scotch thistle, bull
thistle, elk thistle.

00:39:07.870 --> 00:39:10.990 align:middle line:84%
Thistles are a member of
the asteraceae family.

00:39:10.990 --> 00:39:14.530 align:middle line:84%
They're actually a relative
of lettuce and sunflower,

00:39:14.530 --> 00:39:18.070 align:middle line:84%
but they're a very, very
close relative of artichokes.

00:39:18.070 --> 00:39:19.360 align:middle line:90%
They're the ancestor.

00:39:19.360 --> 00:39:21.610 align:middle line:84%
In the springtime
with a pair of gloves,

00:39:21.610 --> 00:39:24.650 align:middle line:84%
you could pull the thistle
up, and there's an edible root

00:39:24.650 --> 00:39:25.450 align:middle line:90%
there.

00:39:25.450 --> 00:39:26.866 align:middle line:84%
It's really quite
good, and if you

00:39:26.866 --> 00:39:29.020 align:middle line:84%
get a thistle when
it's very young,

00:39:29.020 --> 00:39:32.860 align:middle line:84%
the flower hasn't opened
yet, you could cut this open,

00:39:32.860 --> 00:39:35.470 align:middle line:84%
and you'd have a tiny, tiny
little artichoke heart.

00:39:35.470 --> 00:39:38.650 align:middle line:84%
So maybe you want to pull it up,
but you might as well eat it.

00:39:38.650 --> 00:39:40.540 align:middle line:84%
It's something that
Lewis and Clark often

00:39:40.540 --> 00:39:44.080 align:middle line:84%
survived off of when they
were traveling to the Pacific

00:39:44.080 --> 00:39:46.270 align:middle line:90%
Northwest.

00:39:46.270 --> 00:39:48.820 align:middle line:84%
People often walk
by crab apples,

00:39:48.820 --> 00:39:51.834 align:middle line:84%
thinking they're insignificant
because they're small,

00:39:51.834 --> 00:39:53.500 align:middle line:84%
and then they'll go
to the grocery store

00:39:53.500 --> 00:39:55.990 align:middle line:84%
and buy commercial
apples imported

00:39:55.990 --> 00:39:59.037 align:middle line:84%
from some other continent
for a high price

00:39:59.037 --> 00:40:01.120 align:middle line:84%
when they might have
something even more delicious

00:40:01.120 --> 00:40:02.440 align:middle line:90%
in their yard.

00:40:02.440 --> 00:40:04.940 align:middle line:10%
Apples are members
of the rose family,

00:40:04.940 --> 00:40:08.170 align:middle line:10%
so they're a relative of
cherries, peaches, apricots.

00:40:08.170 --> 00:40:12.100 align:middle line:84%
So eating apples cleans your
teeth, freshens your breath.

00:40:12.100 --> 00:40:15.250 align:middle line:84%
They also can be a folk
remedy for stopping diarrhea.

00:40:15.250 --> 00:40:19.120 align:middle line:84%
So before you disdain those
crab apples, take a bite.

00:40:19.120 --> 00:40:20.360 align:middle line:90%
Give it a try.

00:40:20.360 --> 00:40:23.450 align:middle line:90%
You might have a winner.

00:40:23.450 --> 00:40:26.410 align:middle line:84%
Now, certainly not
all plants are edible.

00:40:26.410 --> 00:40:28.570 align:middle line:10%
There are some that
are very poisonous,

00:40:28.570 --> 00:40:32.620 align:middle line:10%
and this plant looks like some
poisonous plants, including

00:40:32.620 --> 00:40:34.660 align:middle line:10%
poison hemlock
and water hemlock,

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:38.200 align:middle line:10%
but the good news is
this is an edible plant.

00:40:38.200 --> 00:40:42.160 align:middle line:84%
It's wild carrot, also
known as Queen Anne's lace.

00:40:42.160 --> 00:40:45.460 align:middle line:84%
And there's a legend about a
queen that lived, I believe,

00:40:45.460 --> 00:40:48.840 align:middle line:84%
in the 1700s, and
she was making lace,

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:51.970 align:middle line:84%
and she pricked her
finger, and a drop of blood

00:40:51.970 --> 00:40:52.900 align:middle line:90%
fell upon her lace.

00:40:52.900 --> 00:40:57.040 align:middle line:84%
So do you see one little tiny
either pink, purple, or red

00:40:57.040 --> 00:40:59.290 align:middle line:90%
flower at the center?

00:40:59.290 --> 00:41:02.350 align:middle line:10%
So this is actually the
ancestor of carrots.

00:41:02.350 --> 00:41:05.420 align:middle line:10%
So if you pull this plant
up out of the ground,

00:41:05.420 --> 00:41:06.980 align:middle line:10%
you would have a little root.

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:09.100 align:middle line:84%
It's not going to be
as big or as tender

00:41:09.100 --> 00:41:11.960 align:middle line:84%
as carrots that you grow in
the garden or buy at the store,

00:41:11.960 --> 00:41:13.810 align:middle line:84%
but it is edible
and can be cooked,

00:41:13.810 --> 00:41:18.100 align:middle line:84%
and certainly the leaves
make a really nice feather

00:41:18.100 --> 00:41:19.990 align:middle line:90%
to put in your cap.

00:41:19.990 --> 00:41:24.520 align:middle line:84%
You can juice the leaves, make
them into a salad, as well.

00:41:24.520 --> 00:41:26.380 align:middle line:84%
One tree that's really
easy to recognize,

00:41:26.380 --> 00:41:30.250 align:middle line:84%
because it keeps its leaves
all winter, are pine trees.

00:41:30.250 --> 00:41:33.100 align:middle line:84%
So we are not able to
digest pine needles.

00:41:33.100 --> 00:41:35.440 align:middle line:84%
They're very sharp
and fibrous, but they

00:41:35.440 --> 00:41:38.950 align:middle line:84%
could be made into a tea,
or in a survival situation,

00:41:38.950 --> 00:41:42.100 align:middle line:90%
you could chew them up.

00:41:42.100 --> 00:41:46.360 align:middle line:84%
You would extract simple
sugars and vitamin C,

00:41:46.360 --> 00:41:47.971 align:middle line:84%
and then you could
spit out the pulp.

00:41:47.971 --> 00:41:49.720 align:middle line:84%
That could save your
life if you were ever

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:51.580 align:middle line:90%
stranded in the wilderness.

00:41:51.580 --> 00:41:54.730 align:middle line:84%
We also know that you
could cut out a portion,

00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:58.840 align:middle line:84%
and take that inner tender
bark, and boil it like noodles,

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:03.820 align:middle line:84%
and could be a super
delicious, nourishing treat.

00:42:03.820 --> 00:42:06.860 align:middle line:84%
This wild plant
is very important.

00:42:06.860 --> 00:42:08.670 align:middle line:90%
It's called lamb's quarter.

00:42:08.670 --> 00:42:11.080 align:middle line:10%
It's also known as wild spinach.

00:42:11.080 --> 00:42:13.360 align:middle line:10%
So lamb's quarter
is totally edible.

00:42:13.360 --> 00:42:16.330 align:middle line:10%
Anything you do with spinach
you can do with lamb's quarter,

00:42:16.330 --> 00:42:20.680 align:middle line:10%
whether it be spanokopita or
soup, or salad, or lasagna.

00:42:20.680 --> 00:42:23.410 align:middle line:90%
Lamb's quarter lasagna, anybody?

00:42:23.410 --> 00:42:25.720 align:middle line:84%
This is also a
relative of amaranth,

00:42:25.720 --> 00:42:27.910 align:middle line:90%
and quinoa, and beets.

00:42:27.910 --> 00:42:33.070 align:middle line:84%
And so in the autumn, you get
these tiny little black seeds.

00:42:33.070 --> 00:42:35.920 align:middle line:84%
You could use
those as a porridge

00:42:35.920 --> 00:42:39.070 align:middle line:84%
or add them to an
extender to your oatmeal.

00:42:39.070 --> 00:42:42.580 align:middle line:84%
They're very nutritious,
high in protein, lysine,

00:42:42.580 --> 00:42:45.580 align:middle line:84%
which is rare in
vegetable based plants.

00:42:45.580 --> 00:42:49.270 align:middle line:84%
And you could also sprout them
as a micro green in the winter

00:42:49.270 --> 00:42:51.410 align:middle line:84%
and have fresh greens
all year round.

00:42:51.410 --> 00:42:55.210 align:middle line:84%
Lamb's quarter-- high in
iron, high in beta carotene.

00:42:55.210 --> 00:42:58.460 align:middle line:84%
So good for you, tastes just
like spinach, and a lot easier

00:42:58.460 --> 00:42:59.260 align:middle line:90%
to grow.

00:42:59.260 --> 00:43:02.190 align:middle line:90%


00:43:02.190 --> 00:43:04.320 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Is there a
good rule of thumb

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:07.650 align:middle line:84%
as to what to tell if
there is a poisonous plant?

00:43:07.650 --> 00:43:11.130 align:middle line:84%
So can you tell specifically
if there's something

00:43:11.130 --> 00:43:15.180 align:middle line:84%
that you shouldn't go after,
or is there any way to tell?

00:43:15.180 --> 00:43:19.370 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I don't want to
suggest that people just tell.

00:43:19.370 --> 00:43:21.840 align:middle line:84%
I mean, there's some
things like beware

00:43:21.840 --> 00:43:25.565 align:middle line:84%
of plants with white sap, but
dandelion has a white sap,

00:43:25.565 --> 00:43:27.810 align:middle line:90%
and it's edible.

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:30.420 align:middle line:84%
Leaves of three, let
it be, like poison ivy.

00:43:30.420 --> 00:43:32.525 align:middle line:84%
But then red clover
has three leaves,

00:43:32.525 --> 00:43:33.650 align:middle line:90%
and it's a wonderful plant.

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:35.820 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It's confusing.

00:43:35.820 --> 00:43:39.360 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I think with mushrooms
they say there are old mushroom

00:43:39.360 --> 00:43:41.430 align:middle line:84%
hunters, and there are
bold mushroom hunters,

00:43:41.430 --> 00:43:44.920 align:middle line:84%
but there are no old
bold mushroom hunters.

00:43:44.920 --> 00:43:47.630 align:middle line:90%
So that's a whole other chapter.

00:43:47.630 --> 00:43:48.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Mushrooms.

00:43:48.430 --> 00:43:51.240 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: I think that really
having some good guidebooks,

00:43:51.240 --> 00:43:53.190 align:middle line:84%
and taking classes,
and don't expect

00:43:53.190 --> 00:43:57.120 align:middle line:84%
to learn all the plants--
try to learn a few a year.

00:43:57.120 --> 00:43:59.280 align:middle line:90%
Go on a walk with an expert.

00:43:59.280 --> 00:44:02.110 align:middle line:10%
And I didn't formulate
this little phone

00:44:02.110 --> 00:44:07.080 align:middle line:10%
app called iPlant, which
it's available for iPhone

00:44:07.080 --> 00:44:07.930 align:middle line:10%
and Android.

00:44:07.930 --> 00:44:08.730 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Great.

00:44:08.730 --> 00:44:11.370 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And it's
pictures concerns,

00:44:11.370 --> 00:44:13.740 align:middle line:84%
like don't use during
pregnancy, or don't

00:44:13.740 --> 00:44:15.240 align:middle line:90%
use with high blood pressure.

00:44:15.240 --> 00:44:17.970 align:middle line:84%
But it has a botanical
description and usually

00:44:17.970 --> 00:44:21.386 align:middle line:84%
three pictures for each
plant, and you can blow it up,

00:44:21.386 --> 00:44:22.760 align:middle line:84%
and it'll tell
you, is it edible?

00:44:22.760 --> 00:44:24.840 align:middle line:90%
Is it medicinal?

00:44:24.840 --> 00:44:26.839 align:middle line:90%
What does the name mean?

00:44:26.839 --> 00:44:29.380 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Can you take a picture
of it and have it identify it?

00:44:29.380 --> 00:44:30.420 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: It doesn't
do that, but there

00:44:30.420 --> 00:44:31.794 align:middle line:84%
are some phone
apps that do that,

00:44:31.794 --> 00:44:34.100 align:middle line:90%
like Leafsnap and plant chat.

00:44:34.100 --> 00:44:35.350 align:middle line:90%
I think there's a couple apps.

00:44:35.350 --> 00:44:37.058 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: And then you
can cross-reference.

00:44:37.058 --> 00:44:40.350 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: You can cross-reference,
but what a noble cause

00:44:40.350 --> 00:44:42.480 align:middle line:84%
to learn the names of
the plants around you.

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:47.130 align:middle line:84%
And I heard the statistic that
the average American recognizes

00:44:47.130 --> 00:44:50.490 align:middle line:84%
over 1,000 logos and
the products they're

00:44:50.490 --> 00:44:54.840 align:middle line:84%
associated with, and yet less
than five plants or five birds.

00:44:54.840 --> 00:44:56.270 align:middle line:90%
So we just need to change that.

00:44:56.270 --> 00:44:57.300 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: True.

00:44:57.300 --> 00:44:58.860 align:middle line:84%
You can see the logo
on the front of a car.

00:44:58.860 --> 00:45:00.526 align:middle line:84%
They don't even have
the name of the car

00:45:00.526 --> 00:45:03.150 align:middle line:84%
any longer because you
identify it through the logo.

00:45:03.150 --> 00:45:04.140 align:middle line:90%
That's true.

00:45:04.140 --> 00:45:08.010 align:middle line:84%
There's a lot of ways-- subtle
ways that we are marketed to.

00:45:08.010 --> 00:45:09.420 align:middle line:84%
Mother nature
doesn't necessarily

00:45:09.420 --> 00:45:10.770 align:middle line:90%
have a marketing department.

00:45:10.770 --> 00:45:12.270 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And you
were saying earlier,

00:45:12.270 --> 00:45:15.990 align:middle line:84%
what is this thing about the
lawns and the pesticides?

00:45:15.990 --> 00:45:20.070 align:middle line:84%
I think it's a belief that
we need to dominate nature,

00:45:20.070 --> 00:45:22.720 align:middle line:84%
that nature is wild,
and free, and feminine.

00:45:22.720 --> 00:45:27.030 align:middle line:84%
We need to control her, and
rein her in, and bridle her,

00:45:27.030 --> 00:45:28.950 align:middle line:90%
or she'll just go wild.

00:45:28.950 --> 00:45:31.710 align:middle line:84%
And again, having
a patch of grass

00:45:31.710 --> 00:45:34.770 align:middle line:84%
might be nice to play
Frisbee with your dog

00:45:34.770 --> 00:45:36.510 align:middle line:90%
or have a picnic on.

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:39.180 align:middle line:84%
It's not like I disdain
grass, but we've

00:45:39.180 --> 00:45:43.200 align:middle line:84%
gotten so over dependent on it,
and a few years ago in Boulder

00:45:43.200 --> 00:45:45.480 align:middle line:90%
we had a dandelion festival.

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:48.450 align:middle line:10%
And we asked city
council, why did

00:45:48.450 --> 00:45:51.000 align:middle line:10%
you think you needed to
spray the dandelions?

00:45:51.000 --> 00:45:54.870 align:middle line:84%
And the answer was, well,
people might trip over them,

00:45:54.870 --> 00:45:56.962 align:middle line:90%
and they might take over.

00:45:56.962 --> 00:45:57.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Take over what?

00:45:57.920 --> 00:45:58.820 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Take over.

00:45:58.820 --> 00:46:01.822 align:middle line:84%
Take over, and proliferate, and
make free food for everybody.

00:46:01.822 --> 00:46:03.030 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Make more dandelions.

00:46:03.030 --> 00:46:03.904 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: There you go.

00:46:03.904 --> 00:46:05.491 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Because
they're such a threat.

00:46:05.491 --> 00:46:07.990 align:middle line:84%
What's wrong with-- they got
such a bad rap, the dandelions.

00:46:07.990 --> 00:46:09.406 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: And we all
know that, when

00:46:09.406 --> 00:46:12.360 align:middle line:84%
you spray herbicides in your
yard, it ends up in the water.

00:46:12.360 --> 00:46:13.890 align:middle line:90%
It ends up in the ground.

00:46:13.890 --> 00:46:17.280 align:middle line:84%
It goes down to the creek,
and it drifts into the air

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:18.690 align:middle line:90%
that we're all breathing.

00:46:18.690 --> 00:46:22.500 align:middle line:84%
So we know better
now, and it's not

00:46:22.500 --> 00:46:24.630 align:middle line:84%
time to start
thinking about this.

00:46:24.630 --> 00:46:26.399 align:middle line:90%
It's time for action.

00:46:26.399 --> 00:46:28.440 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Yes, and which is
why I love what you do.

00:46:28.440 --> 00:46:32.655 align:middle line:84%
And you bring people on walks--
on wild walks, don't you?

00:46:32.655 --> 00:46:35.010 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yes, wild weed
walks all the time.

00:46:35.010 --> 00:46:36.120 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Um--

00:46:36.120 --> 00:46:38.340 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yes, I'm giving
one this weekend,

00:46:38.340 --> 00:46:42.150 align:middle line:84%
and I love doing that
because you never

00:46:42.150 --> 00:46:43.920 align:middle line:84%
look at the world
the same way again.

00:46:43.920 --> 00:46:45.140 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes.

00:46:45.140 --> 00:46:48.540 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Emerson said a weed is
an herb whose virtue has not

00:46:48.540 --> 00:46:50.260 align:middle line:90%
yet been recognized.

00:46:50.260 --> 00:46:52.770 align:middle line:84%
So if I can help people to
respect this plant-- like,

00:46:52.770 --> 00:46:54.702 align:middle line:90%
wow, this could save your life.

00:46:54.702 --> 00:46:56.160 align:middle line:84%
What if you were
lost in the woods?

00:46:56.160 --> 00:46:58.410 align:middle line:84%
And when we look at
our planet right now,

00:46:58.410 --> 00:47:00.450 align:middle line:84%
there's so many
earthly disasters,

00:47:00.450 --> 00:47:05.550 align:middle line:84%
and volcanoes, and hurricanes,
and tornadoes, and flooding.

00:47:05.550 --> 00:47:08.160 align:middle line:84%
And people are
dependent on when's

00:47:08.160 --> 00:47:09.780 align:middle line:90%
Red Cross going to get here?

00:47:09.780 --> 00:47:11.850 align:middle line:84%
And we know that, when
there's a disaster,

00:47:11.850 --> 00:47:15.120 align:middle line:84%
the grocery stores empty
out really quickly.

00:47:15.120 --> 00:47:17.310 align:middle line:84%
Food that needs
to be trucked in--

00:47:17.310 --> 00:47:20.040 align:middle line:84%
if it can't get in, it
really makes a mess,

00:47:20.040 --> 00:47:21.750 align:middle line:84%
and very often food
can't get delivered

00:47:21.750 --> 00:47:23.590 align:middle line:90%
to the people that need it.

00:47:23.590 --> 00:47:25.920 align:middle line:84%
I really think we should
be more empowered,

00:47:25.920 --> 00:47:29.346 align:middle line:84%
and when my kids were
little, I would say--

00:47:29.346 --> 00:47:30.970 align:middle line:84%
they'd say, mom, can
I have some money?

00:47:30.970 --> 00:47:33.360 align:middle line:84%
And I'd say, we're
going to go for a walk.

00:47:33.360 --> 00:47:36.280 align:middle line:84%
I'll give you a quarter for
every plant you can identify,

00:47:36.280 --> 00:47:39.180 align:middle line:84%
$0.50 if you can tell
me the Latin name,

00:47:39.180 --> 00:47:42.090 align:middle line:84%
and $1 if you can
tell me three uses.

00:47:42.090 --> 00:47:44.190 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Oh my goodness,
that's a great game.

00:47:44.190 --> 00:47:46.230 align:middle line:90%
That is a great game.

00:47:46.230 --> 00:47:48.420 align:middle line:84%
I do have a question
about wildfires.

00:47:48.420 --> 00:47:50.340 align:middle line:84%
I've heard that
wildfires are ways

00:47:50.340 --> 00:47:54.850 align:middle line:84%
for the forest to clear
itself and to start room

00:47:54.850 --> 00:47:55.650 align:middle line:90%
for new growth.

00:47:55.650 --> 00:47:59.370 align:middle line:84%
Do you have any
opinions on wildfires?

00:47:59.370 --> 00:48:01.530 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Well, it is
really a terrible thing.

00:48:01.530 --> 00:48:01.770 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: It is.

00:48:01.770 --> 00:48:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: And my heart goes out.

00:48:02.520 --> 00:48:05.040 align:middle line:84%
I certainly know people
that have lost their homes.

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:06.330 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: And the animals.

00:48:06.330 --> 00:48:08.190 align:middle line:10%
>>MARS: Interestingly
enough, I just

00:48:08.190 --> 00:48:12.030 align:middle line:10%
wrote an article on an
herb called fire weed,

00:48:12.030 --> 00:48:14.040 align:middle line:10%
and fire weed is one
of the first herbs

00:48:14.040 --> 00:48:17.850 align:middle line:10%
to come back after
there's been a fire.

00:48:17.850 --> 00:48:21.877 align:middle line:10%
And they used to
call it bomb weed

00:48:21.877 --> 00:48:23.460 align:middle line:10%
because it was one
of the first plants

00:48:23.460 --> 00:48:27.570 align:middle line:10%
to grow in craters where there
had been bombing in England.

00:48:27.570 --> 00:48:31.560 align:middle line:10%
And here you have an area that's
been devastated, and sadness,

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:34.200 align:middle line:10%
and tragedy, and
here comes a plant

00:48:34.200 --> 00:48:38.580 align:middle line:10%
with beautiful pink colors
that is totally edible,

00:48:38.580 --> 00:48:41.080 align:middle line:10%
and it's like a Phoenix rising.

00:48:41.080 --> 00:48:43.870 align:middle line:84%
So I think there's going to
be a lot of fire weed growing,

00:48:43.870 --> 00:48:47.330 align:middle line:84%
and it is edible, and it's
also very anti-inflammatory.

00:48:47.330 --> 00:48:48.900 align:middle line:90%
It makes a wonderful tea--

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:50.160 align:middle line:90%
fire weed honey.

00:48:50.160 --> 00:48:52.710 align:middle line:84%
But that doesn't
mean that it's going

00:48:52.710 --> 00:48:57.390 align:middle line:84%
to replace people's homes and
the habitat of all our animals,

00:48:57.390 --> 00:49:00.450 align:middle line:84%
and it also just shows
us how precious water is,

00:49:00.450 --> 00:49:06.870 align:middle line:90%
because we need to be prepared.

00:49:06.870 --> 00:49:07.900 align:middle line:90%
I mean for everybody.

00:49:07.900 --> 00:49:09.480 align:middle line:90%
Do you have a smoke alarm?

00:49:09.480 --> 00:49:11.820 align:middle line:84%
Do you have a fire
extinguisher in your house?

00:49:11.820 --> 00:49:14.060 align:middle line:90%
Do you know how to use it?

00:49:14.060 --> 00:49:14.940 align:middle line:90%
I took a course.

00:49:14.940 --> 00:49:17.520 align:middle line:84%
You want to spray going
this way along the bottom.

00:49:17.520 --> 00:49:20.520 align:middle line:84%
People don't know, and
when we're in a crisis,

00:49:20.520 --> 00:49:24.300 align:middle line:84%
we often can't think clearly
about the right thing to do.

00:49:24.300 --> 00:49:27.870 align:middle line:84%
Are we cutting the shrubbery
away from our houses?

00:49:27.870 --> 00:49:30.126 align:middle line:10%
So being prepared-- I
just wrote this book

00:49:30.126 --> 00:49:31.250 align:middle line:10%
called "Natural First Aid."

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:31.910 align:middle line:10%
>>LISA: Great, great.

00:49:31.910 --> 00:49:33.326 align:middle line:10%
>>MARS: It has a
lot on what to do

00:49:33.326 --> 00:49:35.610 align:middle line:10%
in cases of fire, and
flooding, and tornado,

00:49:35.610 --> 00:49:37.620 align:middle line:10%
and finding water when
there is no water,

00:49:37.620 --> 00:49:40.680 align:middle line:10%
and a few plants that
grow prolifically

00:49:40.680 --> 00:49:43.920 align:middle line:10%
around the continent to
identify to find food.

00:49:43.920 --> 00:49:44.730 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Food.

00:49:44.730 --> 00:49:46.060 align:middle line:90%
Fantastic.

00:49:46.060 --> 00:49:46.860 align:middle line:90%
That's great.

00:49:46.860 --> 00:49:48.193 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: We need to be survivors.

00:49:48.193 --> 00:49:49.820 align:middle line:84%
All the things that
we thought, well,

00:49:49.820 --> 00:49:52.020 align:middle line:84%
that just happens
in other countries,

00:49:52.020 --> 00:49:55.110 align:middle line:90%
or that just happens in--

00:49:55.110 --> 00:49:57.360 align:middle line:84%
it happens here, and we
can see that it can happen

00:49:57.360 --> 00:49:59.520 align:middle line:90%
in the city and the country.

00:49:59.520 --> 00:50:02.190 align:middle line:84%
And it can happen to million
dollar homes, as well as

00:50:02.190 --> 00:50:06.270 align:middle line:84%
little cabins in
never-never land.

00:50:06.270 --> 00:50:07.680 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Absolutely.

00:50:07.680 --> 00:50:09.349 align:middle line:90%
None of us are immune to it.

00:50:09.349 --> 00:50:10.890 align:middle line:84%
Well, here's a
beautiful video that's

00:50:10.890 --> 00:50:15.645 align:middle line:84%
talking about the barberry root
and the incredible properties.

00:50:15.645 --> 00:50:17.580 align:middle line:90%
Let's take a look.

00:50:17.580 --> 00:50:21.870 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: This is the famous
barberry, mahonia, also known

00:50:21.870 --> 00:50:25.170 align:middle line:84%
as Oregon grape, or
Rocky Mountain grape.

00:50:25.170 --> 00:50:27.750 align:middle line:84%
Maybe they call it
California grape right here.

00:50:27.750 --> 00:50:32.650 align:middle line:10%
So this is in the
berberidaceae family.

00:50:32.650 --> 00:50:35.410 align:middle line:84%
And right now it has
little yellow flowers,

00:50:35.410 --> 00:50:38.610 align:middle line:84%
and you can see it's got
sharp pointed leaves.

00:50:38.610 --> 00:50:40.170 align:middle line:90%
It's a great xeriscape plant.

00:50:40.170 --> 00:50:42.330 align:middle line:84%
It doesn't need a lot
of water, but it's

00:50:42.330 --> 00:50:44.700 align:middle line:84%
the root of this
plant that is used

00:50:44.700 --> 00:50:47.040 align:middle line:84%
for its anti-microbial
properties.

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:50.220 align:middle line:84%
It could be used as a substitute
for golden seal, which

00:50:50.220 --> 00:50:52.030 align:middle line:90%
is endangered in the wild.

00:50:52.030 --> 00:50:56.730 align:middle line:84%
So this plant contains
berberine and is anti-microbial,

00:50:56.730 --> 00:51:00.450 align:middle line:84%
meaning anti-fungal,
anti-viral, antibacterial.

00:51:00.450 --> 00:51:04.350 align:middle line:10%
And the root-- it's a great
remedy internally for skin

00:51:04.350 --> 00:51:06.750 align:middle line:10%
ailments, and then
topically it would

00:51:06.750 --> 00:51:11.850 align:middle line:10%
be good for drying up things
like acne, and psoriasis,

00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:12.880 align:middle line:10%
eczema.

00:51:12.880 --> 00:51:14.370 align:middle line:90%
So I love this plant.

00:51:14.370 --> 00:51:17.100 align:middle line:84%
In the fall, it'll get
blue berries usually,

00:51:17.100 --> 00:51:20.010 align:middle line:84%
or sometimes red berries,
and they're very, very sour.

00:51:20.010 --> 00:51:22.050 align:middle line:84%
When you taste the
sour flavor, it usually

00:51:22.050 --> 00:51:24.310 align:middle line:84%
tells you it's
good for the liver.

00:51:24.310 --> 00:51:27.190 align:middle line:84%
So you can make a lemonade
or a smoothie with it.

00:51:27.190 --> 00:51:30.690 align:middle line:10%
And most Americans are
fixated on two flavors--

00:51:30.690 --> 00:51:34.330 align:middle line:10%
sweet and salty, but
really for ultimate health,

00:51:34.330 --> 00:51:35.790 align:middle line:10%
we want to eat all five flavors.

00:51:35.790 --> 00:51:37.560 align:middle line:10%
So sour is one of them--

00:51:37.560 --> 00:51:41.670 align:middle line:10%
good for the liver
and the gall bladder.

00:51:41.670 --> 00:51:45.376 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: It is amazing how much
you know about just walking

00:51:45.376 --> 00:51:46.500 align:middle line:90%
along the side of the road.

00:51:46.500 --> 00:51:50.280 align:middle line:84%
You just rattled off about
15 things that barberry

00:51:50.280 --> 00:51:52.170 align:middle line:90%
can do-- the famous barberry.

00:51:52.170 --> 00:51:53.380 align:middle line:90%
Love it.

00:51:53.380 --> 00:51:55.140 align:middle line:84%
You absolutely have
beautiful skin,

00:51:55.140 --> 00:51:57.840 align:middle line:84%
and for someone who
is outside so much--

00:51:57.840 --> 00:52:00.210 align:middle line:90%
and you're just ageless.

00:52:00.210 --> 00:52:02.730 align:middle line:10%
Are there great plants
for beautiful skin?

00:52:02.730 --> 00:52:03.550 align:middle line:90%
What are your tips?

00:52:03.550 --> 00:52:04.350 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Thank you.

00:52:04.350 --> 00:52:06.810 align:middle line:84%
Well, skin is
really a reflection

00:52:06.810 --> 00:52:08.850 align:middle line:84%
of what's going on
inside our body,

00:52:08.850 --> 00:52:11.940 align:middle line:84%
and so we always want to think
about the health of our lungs

00:52:11.940 --> 00:52:13.380 align:middle line:90%
and large intestines.

00:52:13.380 --> 00:52:15.150 align:middle line:84%
It's not just about
what you put on,

00:52:15.150 --> 00:52:17.430 align:middle line:84%
but I will share a
little secret with you.

00:52:17.430 --> 00:52:18.850 align:middle line:90%
I do fruit facials.

00:52:18.850 --> 00:52:19.650 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: You do?

00:52:19.650 --> 00:52:22.080 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: In the morning,
I rinse my face,

00:52:22.080 --> 00:52:27.180 align:middle line:84%
and then I apply some kind
of fruit that's in-season.

00:52:27.180 --> 00:52:28.410 align:middle line:90%
Today it was a mulberry.

00:52:28.410 --> 00:52:31.740 align:middle line:84%
I just smushed a mulberry
all over my face.

00:52:31.740 --> 00:52:33.570 align:middle line:90%
Yesterday was a cherry.

00:52:33.570 --> 00:52:35.280 align:middle line:90%
The day before was a peach.

00:52:35.280 --> 00:52:36.960 align:middle line:84%
You never want to
use mangoes, though,

00:52:36.960 --> 00:52:40.510 align:middle line:84%
because mangoes are in
the poison ivy family.

00:52:40.510 --> 00:52:41.430 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Wow.

00:52:41.430 --> 00:52:42.230 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: They are.

00:52:42.230 --> 00:52:43.560 align:middle line:90%
So are cashews.

00:52:43.560 --> 00:52:48.510 align:middle line:10%
You may have heard that alpha
hydroxy citric acid, which

00:52:48.510 --> 00:52:50.430 align:middle line:10%
is one of the hot
ingredients in cosmetics,

00:52:50.430 --> 00:52:51.872 align:middle line:10%
is great for our skin.

00:52:51.872 --> 00:52:53.580 align:middle line:84%
Well, you could buy
a bottle of something

00:52:53.580 --> 00:52:56.010 align:middle line:84%
with alpha hydroxy
citric acid, but you

00:52:56.010 --> 00:52:58.680 align:middle line:84%
might have a fresh peach
or a fresh cucumber

00:52:58.680 --> 00:53:01.030 align:middle line:84%
there that you could
just put it on your skin.

00:53:01.030 --> 00:53:04.040 align:middle line:84%
So it's going to give you
exfoliating properties

00:53:04.040 --> 00:53:06.980 align:middle line:84%
to help digest the
dead layers of skin,

00:53:06.980 --> 00:53:08.560 align:middle line:90%
and it's also nourishing.

00:53:08.560 --> 00:53:12.770 align:middle line:84%
Now, I always hope that the UPS
man doesn't come to the door

00:53:12.770 --> 00:53:16.306 align:middle line:84%
when I have pomegranates
on my face or something,

00:53:16.306 --> 00:53:17.930 align:middle line:84%
but I leave it on
for about 10 minutes,

00:53:17.930 --> 00:53:19.016 align:middle line:90%
and then I rinse it off.

00:53:19.016 --> 00:53:20.390 align:middle line:84%
I think another
thing is standing

00:53:20.390 --> 00:53:23.240 align:middle line:84%
on your head every day, because
when you stand on your head,

00:53:23.240 --> 00:53:25.972 align:middle line:84%
you invert, and you get the
blood to go to your head.

00:53:25.972 --> 00:53:26.930 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Do you do that?

00:53:26.930 --> 00:53:28.310 align:middle line:84%
>>MARS: Yeah, I
did this morning.

00:53:28.310 --> 00:53:29.360 align:middle line:90%
I do almost every day.

00:53:29.360 --> 00:53:31.026 align:middle line:84%
>>LISA: Every day
standing on your head.

00:53:31.026 --> 00:53:32.250 align:middle line:90%
That's the best tip ever.

00:53:32.250 --> 00:53:33.120 align:middle line:90%
I love it.

00:53:33.120 --> 00:53:34.411 align:middle line:90%
What about your beautiful hair?

00:53:34.411 --> 00:53:35.937 align:middle line:84%
You have such shiny,
beautiful hair.

00:53:35.937 --> 00:53:37.020 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Thank you so much.

00:53:37.020 --> 00:53:39.590 align:middle line:10%
Well, according to the
principles of Asian medicine,

00:53:39.590 --> 00:53:43.210 align:middle line:10%
our hair is nourished a lot
by the health of our kidneys.

00:53:43.210 --> 00:53:45.470 align:middle line:10%
And so people who want
to have healthy hair

00:53:45.470 --> 00:53:49.460 align:middle line:10%
might want to think about eating
more black colored foods, not

00:53:49.460 --> 00:53:51.740 align:middle line:10%
things that are dyed
black, but things

00:53:51.740 --> 00:53:54.020 align:middle line:10%
that are black because
they're so high in minerals.

00:53:54.020 --> 00:54:00.080 align:middle line:10%
So things like wild rice,
black quinoa, black chia seeds,

00:54:00.080 --> 00:54:03.320 align:middle line:10%
black beans, black seaweed.

00:54:03.320 --> 00:54:05.915 align:middle line:84%
Also nettles is great for your
hair, but standing on your head

00:54:05.915 --> 00:54:07.040 align:middle line:90%
is good for your hair, too.

00:54:07.040 --> 00:54:09.800 align:middle line:84%
Pumpkin seeds and sunflower
seeds are good for your hair.

00:54:09.800 --> 00:54:13.850 align:middle line:10%
So our physical body is
really just a manifestation

00:54:13.850 --> 00:54:17.850 align:middle line:10%
of our inner health, and
sometimes people think,

00:54:17.850 --> 00:54:21.110 align:middle line:10%
oh, we don't want to be
vain or put too much energy,

00:54:21.110 --> 00:54:24.230 align:middle line:10%
but yet we love a beautiful
sunset or beautiful flowers.

00:54:24.230 --> 00:54:28.550 align:middle line:84%
So why not wear beautiful
colors, and eat beautiful food,

00:54:28.550 --> 00:54:31.730 align:middle line:84%
and put our consciousness
in places of beauty?

00:54:31.730 --> 00:54:33.590 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: Yes, I can see that.

00:54:33.590 --> 00:54:35.750 align:middle line:84%
It really works for
you, but you live

00:54:35.750 --> 00:54:39.770 align:middle line:84%
in such harmony with the land
that that makes so much sense

00:54:39.770 --> 00:54:41.140 align:middle line:90%
that it's an extension of you.

00:54:41.140 --> 00:54:41.940 align:middle line:90%
>>MARS: Thank you.

00:54:41.940 --> 00:54:43.920 align:middle line:90%
>>LISA: So it's wonderful.

